# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrical-injury
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis may be a sign of a more serious medical problem, such as connective tissue diseases and diseases associated with central cyanosis.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Other causative conditions include infections, toxicities, antiphospholipid syndrome, cryoglobulinemia, neoplasms.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] In these cases, the observed cutaneous changes are known as "secondary acrocyanosis".
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] They may have a less symmetric distribution and may be associated with pain and tissue loss.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis is characterized by peripheral cyanosis: persistent cyanosis of the hands, feet, knees, or face.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The extremities often are cold and clammy and may exhibit some swelling (especially in warmer weather).
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The palms and soles exhibit a wide range of sweating from moderately moist to profuse, but all peripheral pulses should have normal rate, rhythm, and quality.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Exposure to cold temperatures worsens the cyanosis, while it often improves on warming.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Aside from the color changes, patients normally are asymptomatic and therefore there is usually no associated pain.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The most common sign, discoloration, usually is what prompts patients to seek medical care.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The precise mechanism of acrocyanosis is not known.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The current line of thinking goes that vasospasms in the cutaneous arteries and arterioles produce cyanotic discoloration, while compensatory dilatation in the postcapillary venules causes sweating.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Arteriovenous subpapillary plexus shunting also occurs.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Persistent vasoconstriction at the precapillary sphincter creates a local hypoxic environment, thus releasing adenosine into the capillary bed.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Vasospasms force adenosine to enter the capillary bed, where it vasodilates the postcapillary venules.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Such differences in vessel tone create a countercurrent exchange system that attempts to retain heat.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Profuse sweating would then be caused by an overwhelmed countercurrent exchange system.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] In addition to adenosine, other hormones may contribute to acrocyanosis such as increase blood levels of serotonin.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] This would seem to support case studies reporting acrocyanosis as an unusual side effect for pediatric patients taking tricyclic antidepressants, as these medications can inhibit the reuptake of serotonin and thus increase their blood concentrations.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis has been reported in association with many other medications and substances.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis is diagnosed clinically, based on a medical history and physical examination; laboratory studies or imaging studies are not necessary.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The normal peripheral pulses rule out peripheral arterial occlusive disease, where arterial narrowing limits blood flow to the extremities.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Pulse oximetry will show a normal oxygen saturation.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Unlike the closely related Raynaud's phenomenon, cyanosis is continually persistent.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] In addition, there is usually no associated trophic skin changes, localized pain, or ulcerations.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Capillaroscopy and other laboratory methods may be helpful but only complement clinical diagnosis in unclear cases, especially when connective tissue disorders may be present.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] There is no standard medical or surgical treatment for acrocyanosis, and treatment, other than reassurance and avoidance of cold, is usually unnecessary.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] The patient is reassured that no serious illness is present.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] A sympathectomy would alleviate the cyanosis by disrupting the fibers of the sympathetic nervous system to the area.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] However, such an extreme procedure would rarely be appropriate.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Treatment with vasoactive drugs is not recommended but traditionally is mentioned as optional.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] However, there is little, if any, empirical evidence that vasoactive drugs (α-adrenergic blocking agents or calcium channel blockers) are effective.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] While there is no cure for acrocyanosis, patients otherwise have excellent prognosis.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Unless acrocyanosis results from another condition (e.g. malignancy, antiphospholipid syndrome, atherosclerosis, acute ischemic limb, bacterial endocarditis), there is no associated increased risk of disease or death, and there are no known complications.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Aside from the discoloration, there are no other symptoms: no pain, and no loss of function.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Patients can expect to lead normal lives.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] In secondary acrocyanosis treatment of the primary condition defines outcomes.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Although there is no definitive reporting on its incidence, acrocyanosis shows prevalence in children and young adults than in patients thirty years of age or older.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Epidemiological data suggests that cold climate, outdoor occupation, and low body mass index are significant risk factors for developing acrocyanosis.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] As expected, acrocyanosis would be more prevalent in women than in men due to differences in BMI.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] However, the incidence rate of acrocyanosis often decreases with increasing age, regardless of regional climate.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] It completely resolves in many women after menopause implying significant hormonal influences.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] There is some evidence that many cases of idiopathic acrocyanosis are in some way related to a disorder of estrogen, or aromatase.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Around 50% of patients with POTS experience acrocyanosis of their legs while standing still.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis is common initially after delivery in preterm and full term newborns.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Intervention is typically not required as it is seen as a normal finding.
[src:electrical-injury/acrocyanosis] Acrocyanosis can also return in a newborn if a baby is cold, such as after a bath, and is considered normal as well.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] An **adverse drug reaction** (**ADR**) is an unintended medical event, which can potentially be associated with taking a medication.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] It can be disadvantageous or beneficial for the patient.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] ADRs may occur following a single dose or prolonged administration of a drug or may result from the combination of two or more drugs.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The meaning of this term differs from the term "side effect" because side effects are proven by thorough investigation to have relationship to the drug.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The study of ADRs is the concern of the field known as *pharmacovigilance*.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] An adverse event (AE) refers to any unexpected and inappropriate occurrence at the time a drug is used, whether or not the event is associated with the administration of the drug.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] An ADR is a special type of AE in which a causative relationship can be shown or is suspected.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] ADRs are only one type of medication-related harm.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Another type of medication-related harm type includes not taking prescribed medications, known as non-adherence.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Non-adherence to medications can lead to death and other negative outcomes.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Adverse drug reactions require the use of a medication.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] They are dose-related and usually mild, although they may be serious or even fatal (e.g.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Such reactions are usually due to inappropriate dosage, especially when drug elimination is impaired.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] may be applied to minor type A reactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Types A and B were proposed in the 1970s, and the other types were proposed subsequently when the first two proved insufficient to classify ADRs.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Other types of adverse drug reactions are Type C, Type D, Type E, and Type F.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Type C was categorized for chronic adverse drug reactions, Type D for delayed adverse drug reactions, Type E for withdrawal adverse drug reactions, and Type F for failure of therapy as an adverse drug reaction.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Adverse drug reactions can also be categorized using time-relatedness, dose-relatedness, and susceptibility, which collectively are called the DoTS classification.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Severity is a measure of the intensity of the adverse event in question.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The terms "severe" and "serious", when applied to adverse events, are technically very different.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] They are easily confused but can not be used interchangeably, requiring care in usage.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Seriousness usually indicates patient outcome (such as negative outcomes including disability, long-term effects, and death).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In adverse drug reactions, the seriousness of the reaction is important for reporting.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Some ocular antihypertensives cause systemic effects, although they are administered locally as eye drops, since a fraction escapes to the systemic circulation.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Various diseases, especially those that cause renal or hepatic insufficiency, may alter drug metabolism.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Resources are available that report changes in a drug's metabolism due to disease states.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The Medication Appropriateness Tool for Comorbid Health Conditions in Dementia (MATCH-D) criteria warns that people with dementia are more likely to experience adverse effects, and that they are less likely to be able to reliably report symptoms.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Pharmacogenomics includes how genes can predict potential adverse drug reactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] However, pharmacogenomics is not limited to adverse events (of any type), but also looks at how genes may impact other responses to medications, such as low/no effect or expected/normal responses (especially based on drug metabolism).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Abnormal drug metabolism may be due to inherited factors of either Phase I oxidation or Phase II conjugation.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Phase I reactions include metabolism by cytochrome P450.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Patients have abnormal metabolism by cytochrome P450 due to either inheriting abnormal alleles or due to drug interactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Tables are available to check for drug interactions due to P450 interactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Inheriting abnormal butyrylcholinesterase (pseudocholinesterase) may affect metabolism of drugs such as succinylcholine.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Inheriting abnormal *N*-acetyltransferase which conjugated some drugs to facilitate excretion may affect the metabolism of drugs such as isoniazid, hydralazine, and procainamide.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Inheriting abnormal thiopurine *S*-methyltransferase may affect the metabolism of the thiopurine drugs mercaptopurine and azathioprine.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Protein binding interactions are usually transient and mild until a new steady state is achieved.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] These are mainly for drugs without much first-pass liver metabolism.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Some drug interactions with warfarin are due to changes in protein binding.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The risk of drug interactions is increased with polypharmacy, especially in older adults.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Two or more drugs that contribute to the same mechanism in the body can have additive toxic or adverse effects.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] One example of this is multiple medications administered concurrently that prolong the QT interval, such as antiarrhythmics like sotalol and some macrolide antibiotics, such as systemic azithromycin.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Another example of additive effects for adverse drug reactions is in serotonin toxicity (serotonin syndrome).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] If medications that cause increased serotonin levels are combined, they can cause serotonin toxicity (though therapeutic doses of one agent that increases serotonin levels can cause serotonin toxicity in certain cases and individuals).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Some of the medications that can contribute to serotonin toxicity include MAO inhibitors, SSRIs, and tricyclic antidepressants.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Some medications can either inhibit or induce key drug metabolizing enzymes or drug transporters, which when combined with other medications that utilize the same proteins can lead to either toxic or sub-therapeutic adverse effects.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Additionally, Clarithromycin is a permeability glycoprotein (P-gp) efflux pump inhibitor, which when given with apixaban (a substrate for P-gp) will lead to increased absorption of apixaban, resulting in the same adverse effects as with CYP3A4 inhibition.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Causality assessment is used to determine the likelihood that a drug caused a suspected ADR.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] There are a number of different methods used to judge causation, including the Naranjo algorithm, the Venulet algorithm and the WHO causality term assessment criteria.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Each have pros and cons associated with their use and most require some level of expert judgement to apply.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] An ADR should not be labeled as 'certain' unless the ADR abates with a challenge-dechallenge-rechallenge protocol (stopping and starting the agent in question).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The chronology of the onset of the suspected ADR is important, as another substance or factor may be implicated as a cause; co-prescribed medications and underlying psychiatric conditions may be factors in the ADR.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Assigning causality to a specific agent often proves difficult, unless the event is found during a clinical study or large databases are used.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Both methods have difficulties and can be fraught with error.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Even in clinical studies, some ADRs may be missed as large numbers of test individuals are required to find a specific adverse drug reaction, especially for rare ADRs.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Psychiatric ADRs are often missed as they are grouped together in the questionnaires used to assess the population.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Many countries have official bodies that monitor drug safety and reactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] On an international level, the WHO runs the Uppsala Monitoring Centre.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The European Union runs the European Medicines Agency (EMA).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In the United States, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) is responsible for monitoring post-marketing studies.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The FDA has a reporting system called the FDA Adverse Event Reporting System, where individuals can report adverse drug events.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Healthcare professionals, consumers, and the pharmaceutical industry can all submit information to this system.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] For health products marketed in Canada, a branch of Health Canada called The Canada Vigilance Program is responsible for surveillance.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Both healthcare professionals and consumers can report to this program.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In Australia, the Therapeutic Goods Administration (TGA) conducts postmarket monitoring of therapeutic products.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In the UK, a monitoring system called the Yellow Card Scheme was established in 1964.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] The Yellow Card Scheme was set up to surveil medications and other health products.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] A study by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) found that in 2011, sedatives and hypnotics were a leading source for adverse drug events seen in the hospital setting.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Approximately 2.8% of all ADEs present on admission and 4.4% of ADEs that originated during a hospital stay were caused by a sedative or hypnotic drug.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] A second study by AHRQ found that in 2011, the most common specifically identified causes of adverse drug events that originated during hospital stays in the U.S. were steroids, antibiotics, opiates/narcotics, and anticoagulants.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Patients treated in urban teaching hospitals had higher rates of ADEs involving antibiotics and opiates/narcotics compared to those treated in urban nonteaching hospitals.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Those treated in private, nonprofit hospitals had higher rates of most ADE causes compared to patients treated in public or private, for-profit hospitals.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Medication related harm (MRH) is common after hospital discharge in older adults, but methodological inconsistencies between studies and a paucity of data on risk factors limits clear understanding of the epidemiology.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] There was a wide range in incidence, from 0.4% to 51.2% of participants, and 35% to 59% of harm was preventable.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Medication related harm incidence within 30 days after discharge ranged from 167 to 500 events per 1,000 individuals discharged (17–51% of individuals).
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In the U.S., females had a higher rate of ADEs involving opiates and narcotics than males in 2011, while male patients had a higher rate of anticoagulant ADEs.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] Nearly 8 in 1,000 adults aged 65 years or older experienced one of the four most common ADEs (steroids, antibiotics, opiates/narcotics, and anticoagulants) during hospitalization.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] A study showed that 48% of patients had an adverse drug reaction to at least one drug, and pharmacist involvement helps to pick up adverse drug reactions.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] In 2012, McKinsey & Company concluded that the cost of the 50-100 million preventable error-related adverse drug events would be between US$18–115 billion.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] An article published in The Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) in 2016 reported adverse drug event statistics from emergency departments around the United States in 2013-2014.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] From this article, an estimated prevalence of adverse drug events that were presented to the emergency department (ED) was 4 events out of every 1000 people.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] This article reported that 57.1% of these adverse drug events presented to the ED were in females.
[src:electrical-injury/adverse-drug-reaction] As well, out of all of the adverse drug events presented to the emergency department documented in this article, 17.6% were from anticoagulants, 16.1% were from antibiotics, and 13.3% from diabetic agents.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Typically, sinus barotrauma is preceded by an upper respiratory tract infection or allergy.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The affected person has a sudden sharp facial pain or headache during descent, which increases as the aircraft approaches ground level.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The pain can ultimately become disabling unless the ambient pressure is reversed.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The pressure difference causes the mucosal lining of the sinuses to become swollen and submucosal bleeding follows with further difficulties ventilating the sinus, especially if the orifices are involved.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Ultimately fluid or blood will fill the space.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] In most cases of sinus barotrauma, localized pain to the frontal area is the predominant symptom.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] This is due to pain originating from the frontal sinus, it being above the brow bones.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Less common is pain referred to the temporal, occipital, or retrobulbar region.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Epistaxis or serosanguineous secretion from the nose may occur.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Neurological symptoms may affect the adjacent fifth cranial nerve and especially the infraorbital nerve.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The pathology of sinus barotrauma is directly related to Boyle's law, which states that the volume of a gas is inversely proportional to the pressure on it, when temperature is constant (P1 × V1 = P2 × V2).
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Two types of acute barotrauma are observed: squeeze and reverse squeeze.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] On ascent, the air in the paranasal sinuses will expand according to Boyle's law, contracting during descent.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Normally, the sinuses drain into the nasal cavity through small ostia, which permit mucociliary clearance and ventilation that equilibrates pressure.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] However, when the opening is obstructed due to inflammation, polyps, mucosal thickening, anatomical abnormalities, or other lesions, pressure equilibration is impossible.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Squeeze is produced on descent when trapped air in the sinuses contracts and produces negative pressure.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The pressure differentials are directed to the center of the sinuses producing mucosal edema, transudation, and mucosal-or submucosal-hematoma, leading to further occlusion of the sinus ostium.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The sinus will fill with fluid or blood unless the pressure differential is neutralized.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] If the outlet is blocked during ascent, the situation is reversed and "reverse squeeze" appears.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Pressure inside the sinus increases, affecting the walls of the sinus and producing pain or epistaxis.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The majority of episodes of sinus barotrauma occur in the frontal sinuses with pain localized over the frontal area.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Possible explanations for this might be the relatively long and delicate nasofrontal duct that connects the narrow frontal recess with the frontal sinuses.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Barotrauma located in the maxillary, ethmoidal, or sphenoid sinuses is observed less frequently and appears when the ostia are blocked; the majority of cases are probably caused by an acute upper respiratory tract infection.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] The magnitude of the pressure difference needed to produce a barotrauma probably shows great individual variation and is related to the size of the sinus ostium and the rate of ambient pressure change.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Due to this, even commercial flying may produce severe cases of barotraumas, although most of the cases are observed in high performance aircraft with lower pressurized cabins.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Most cases occur in scuba divers and fliers, and is easily diagnosed when presented to physicians immediately after exposure.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] On the other hand, the problem may remain undiagnosed when the history fails to relate the symptoms to exposure to environmental pressure changes or if the focus is on other etiologies.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Weissman defined three grades of sinus barotraumas according to symptomatology.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Mild cases of barotrauma are readily treated by topical decongestants and painkillers.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] In severe cases or cases resistant to local treatment, functional endoscopic sinus surgery is indicated in order to re-establish drainage and ventilation of the sinuses.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] This treatment has shown good results in aviators who have recurrent sinus barotrauma.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Computer-aided surgery has re-established the drainage of affected sinuses, especially with regard to the sphenoid sinuses.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] When the sphenoids were entered endoscopically, mucosal petechia and hematoma were clearly seen.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Sinus barotrauma or aerosinusitis has been known since the early development of aviation medicine.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] However, it was during World War II that the subject first received serious attention and the pathogenesis of the disease was understood to be due to exposure to high altitude flights.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Rapid altitude changes with accompanying changes in ambient pressure exposed the aircrews to an increasing number of episodes of sinus barotrauma.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Referred pain from barosinusitis to the maxilla consists about one-fifth of in-flight barodontalgia (i.e., pain in the oral cavity caused by barometric pressure change) cases.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosinusitis] Although the environment of fighter pilots produces the most stressful barometric changes, commercial flying has changed the picture of the disease.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] An **aerosol frostbite of the skin** is an injury to the body caused by the pressurized gas within an aerosol spray cooling quickly, with the sudden drop in temperature sufficient to cause frostbite to the applied area.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Medical studies have noted an increase of this practice, known as "frosting", in pediatric and teenage patients.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Adiabatic expansion and/or evaporative cooling (with a low boiling temperature) causes the gas to rapidly cool on exit from the aerosol applier.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] In freeze sprays, a controlled amount of this cooling is useful.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Uncontrolled cooling, however, can result in freeze burns to the skin.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] According to controlled laboratory experiments, the gas from a typical deodorant spray can is able to reduce skin temperature by up to sixty degrees Celsius.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] The form of injury is freezing of the skin, a type of frostbite.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] It is highly advised for those who develop frostbite to seek medical attention.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] In rare cases aerosol-induced burns can be severe enough to necessitate skin grafting.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Depending on the duration of exposure aerosol-induced frostbite can vary in depth.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Most injuries of this type only affect the epidermis, the outermost layer of skin.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] However, if contact with the aerosol is prolonged the skin will freeze further and deeper layers of tissue will be affected, causing a more serious burn that reaches the dermis, destroys nerves, and increases the risk of infection and scarring.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] When the skin thaws, pain and severe discomfort can occur in the affected area.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] There may be a smell of aerosol products such as deodorant around the affected area, the injury may itch or be painful, the skin may freeze and become hardened, blisters may form on the area, and the flesh can become red and swollen.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] The most common cause of aerosol burns is patients' spraying deodorants for prolonged periods of time in close proximity to their skin.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] This practice is more common in younger persons such as teenagers and can be referred to as "frosting" or having a "frosty".
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Injuries such as these are often self-inflicted, and depression should be considered as an underlying cause.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] However, some do it for social media attention in viral video posts or after peer pressure, the "Deodorant Challenge" being analogous to the Cinnamon challenge and Tide Pod challenge.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] However, some do it due to influence by their peers as a way of "impressing" them, with the "Aerosol Challenge" gaining popularity alongside the "Cinnamon Challenge" and "Chubby Bunny" contests as trends in dangerous peer-pressure-induced self-harm.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] A person can cause frostbite by accidental prolonged contact, using an aerosol on one place for too long.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] This is often done with deodorants, but other products such as asthma inhalers are also common causes of injury.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Injuries are especially common with younger children who "try it out" not knowing all the possible dermatological effects.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] In rarer cases aerosol burns are reported to have been caused by air fresheners and other compressed aerosol canisters exploding.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Fluorinated hydrocarbon (fluorocarbon) aerosol propellants can be abused, as with solvents.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] A common form is huffing as a means of intoxication.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] When inhaled, aerosols can cause the same frostbite as on other parts of the body.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] The National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA) has published various resources on the internet warning of the effects of this abuse.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Some aerosol burns are intentionally self-inflicted, the reasons being emotional/psychological.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Household aerosol products such as air fresheners and deodorants can be a convenient, easily available means to satisfy the compulsions.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] Various methods of treatment are used, depending greatly on the length of exposure and other factors.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] There are documented cases using both conservative and invasive treatments, including skin grafting and/or the application of nonadhesive dressing alongside topical corticosteroids to reduce inflammation.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] However, the use of steroids may exacerbate fungal infections if the aerosol product used is an antifungal medicine.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] In some patients postinflammatory hypopigmentation or hyperpigmentation may result in the months after initial injury, and ultraviolet protection such as sunscreen is essential to prevent an elevated risk of skin cancer in the damaged tissues.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] The pain caused by these burns is often intense and can be prolonged, making a pain management plan important.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] This often includes short term prescriptions of painkillers.
[src:electrical-injury/aerosol-burn] In the case of self-harm induced injury the underlying mental health aspects should be treated as with all self-inflicted injuries.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In agriculture, fences are used to keep animals out of, or inside, an area.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] They can be made from a wide variety of materials, depending on terrain, location, and animals to be confined.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Most **agricultural fencing** averages about 4 feet (1.2 m) high, and in some places, the height and construction of fences designed to hold livestock is mandated by law.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A **fencerow** is the strip of land by a fence that is left uncultivated.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] It may be a hedgerow or a shelterbelt (windbreak) or a refuge for native plants.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] If not too narrow, it acts as a habitat corridor.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Historically, throughout most of the world, domesticated livestock would roam freely and were fenced out of areas such as gardens or crop fields where they were unwanted.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Over time, especially where crop agriculture became dominant, and the population density of both humans and animals was significant, livestock owners were required to fence their animals in.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The earliest fences were made of available materials, usually stone or wood, and these materials are still used for some fences today.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In areas where field stones are plentiful, fences have been built over the years as stones are removed from fields during tillage and crop planting.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The stones were placed on the field edge to get them out of the way.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In time, the piles of stones grew high and wide.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In other areas, fences were constructed of timber.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Log fences or split-rail fences were simple fences constructed in newly cleared areas by stacking log rails.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Earth could also be used as a fence; an example was what is now called the sunken fence, or "ha-ha," a type of wall built by digging a ditch with one steep side (which animals cannot scale) and one sloped side (where the animals roam).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The tradition of fencing out unwanted livestock prevails even today in some sparsely populated areas.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] For example, until the mid-20th century, most states in the American West were called "open range" ("fence out") states, in contrast to Eastern and Midwestern states, which long had "fence in" laws requiring owners to confine livestock.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Though the open range was part of the western tradition, over time it was limited long before it was eliminated; first came an obligation to keep cattle from roaming onto state and federal highways, where collisions with fast-moving cars and trucks posed a public safety hazard.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In addition, voters could voluntarily designate certain heavily farmed areas as "herd district," where livestock needed to be fenced in.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] This process also became popular in areas where the development of hobby farms created conflicts between large and small landowners.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Over time, court cases steadily limited the application of open-range law to the point that, in many parts of the American West, it is the exception rather than the rule today.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In the United Kingdom, the law differs between private land and common land.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] On private land, it is the owner's responsibility to fence livestock in, but landowners bordering a common are responsible for fencing the common's livestock out.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Additionally, railways in the UK are fenced to keep livestock and people out, as required, unlike in many other countries.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Either Network Rail or the landowner is responsible for maintaining the fences.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The principle of wire fences is that they are supported mainly by tension, being stretched between heavy strutted or guy-wired posts at ends, corners, and ideally at intervals in longer stretches (every 50 to 300 meters, 150 to 1000 feet).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Between these braced posts are additional smaller wooden or metal posts which keep the wires spaced and upright, usually 3 to 6 meters (10 to 20 feet) apart, depending on the style of fencing used.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Traditionally, wire fencing material is made of galvanized mild steel, but galvanized high-tensile steel is now also used in many places.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Wire fences are typically run on wooden posts, either from trees commercially grown in plantations or (particularly in the American West) cut from public lands.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] When less expensive or more readily available than wood, steel T-posts or star posts are used, usually alternating every 2 to 5 steel posts with a more stable wood post.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Non-electrified wire is attached to wooden posts using fencing staples (for intermediate posts, these are fitted loosely, not gripping the wire).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Non-electrified wire is held on T-posts by wire "clips" made of smooth galvanized wire that wrap around the back of the post and hook onto the wire on either side.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Other than in a truly desert climate, use of rot-resistant wooden posts or steel posts is advised.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In the United States, wood with natural rot resistance, such as oak and juniper, was often used until it became scarce in the 1950s.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Then, chemically treated pine and spruce posts became prevalent, and they are also widely used in the United Kingdom, together with chestnut.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Creosote, pentachlorophenol, and chromated copper arsenate are all widely used in the US and elsewhere for treatment (although some of these chemicals are subject to legal controls).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The Industrial Revolution brought the first barbed wire (also "barbwire" or just "barb") fences, which were widely used after their introduction in the mid-19th century.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] This technology made it economically feasible to fence rangeland for the first time.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In the United States, the introduction of barbed wire contributed to the range wars of that century, as various ranch interests attempted to use barbed wire fences to claim exclusive access to the best pasture and water resources, including those lands in the public domain.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] It also exacerbated tensions between cattle ranchers and crop farmers, particularly when access to water was at issue.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Many manufacturers have made barbed wire in an almost endless variety of styles.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] For the most part, these were functionally identical.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The differences reflected peculiarities of each manufacturing process rather than the deliberate design of the end product.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Some enthusiasts collect sections of unusual barbed wire.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The traditional barbed wire used since the late 19th century and into the present day was made from two mild steel wires twisted together, usually of about 12 or 14 gauge, with about 15–30 twists per meter.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Steel barbs were attached every 10–20 cm (3.9–7.9 in).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Barbs had either two or four points, with the two-point design featuring somewhat heavier, longer barbs.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The relative merits of two-point vs. four-point barbed wire are the subject of deeply held views among many farmers and ranchers, to the extent that both types are still made today.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Typically, four strands of barbed wire, with the lowest strand no more than 12 inches (300 mm) from the ground and the top strand at least 48 inches above the ground, make up a legal fence in the western United States.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Better-quality fences have five strands, older fences often had only three strands, and just two strands are widely used in Britain if only adult cattle are being contained.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Other variations exist, depending on local laws and the purpose of the fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Barbed wire is particularly effective for containing cattle.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In pastures containing both cattle and sheep, one or two strands of barbed wire are used in conjunction with woven wire to both discourage cattle from reaching over the top of a fence and to keep sheep from crawling under.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Though often used in many areas for horses, barbed wire is not advised; its use is considered poor management.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] There is a very high risk of injury occurring when a thin-skinned, fast-moving animal with long legs runs into it or puts a leg through the strands.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Smooth (or plain) wire is essentially the same product as barbed wire with no barbs – either a two-wire twist or a single strand.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Its primary advantage is that it is less likely to cause lacerations and cuts if an animal becomes entangled in it or rubs against it.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] However, animals will readily lean on mild steel smooth wire, stretching it out of shape or loosening it from the posts, and for this reason, it is often used in high-tensile form, which more easily springs back to its original length.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Smooth wire fencing is often used as an inexpensive means to safely contain horses and other animals at high risk of entanglement, usually in conjunction with a line of electric fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Smooth wire is also used to secure fence-post braces and for other uses where barbed wire is not recommended.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] High tensile (H-T or HT) fencing is a special hard, springy steel wire that was introduced in the 1970s and has slowly gained acceptance.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The wire may be a single strand of plain or barbed wire, or woven mesh, and is capable of much higher tension than mild steel.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] It permits the use of wider post spacings and is neither stretched easily by animals, nor by fallen trees or branches.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Because of the wide spacing between posts, thin metal or wooden spacers (or "droppers") may be attached to the wires between posts to maintain that spacing.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Joining HT wire is difficult because of its stiffness and reduced strength when bent sharply.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] However, it may be joined effectively with proprietary clips.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] HT wire is more expensive than mild steel, but because fewer posts are needed, the overall cost of the fencing is usually comparable.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Because it does not stretch, HT wire is less likely to entangle animals.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] However, for the same reason, if an animal becomes entangled or runs into a few strands at high speed, it can be deadly, sometimes referred to as having a "cheese cutter" effect.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Trellising for horticultural purposes is generally constructed from HT wire because it can withstand higher crop loads without breaking or stretching.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Woven and mesh wire fencing material has smooth horizontal wires and vertical wires (called stays).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Wire spacing and height of fence are dependent on which type of animal is being contained.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Agricultural woven wire is identifiable by wire "knots" wrapped around each intersecting wire.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Mesh wire material is spot-welded at each junction.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Woven wire and mesh wire fences are also called square wire, box wire, page wire, sheep fence, or hog fence in the United States, sheep netting or pig netting in Britain, and ringlock in Australia.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Barbed wire fences cannot effectively contain smaller livestock such as pigs, goats, or sheep.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Where these animals are to be fenced, woven wire is used instead, sometimes with one or more strands of barbed wire at the top, and sometimes at the bottom to prevent animals from pushing under.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] For swine, a ground-level barbed wire strand or electrified wire is used as well to prevent digging beneath the fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Woven wire with large openings has some potential hazards.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Large hoofed animals can put a foot through wide gaps while grazing along the fence line or reaching over it, and then become tangled in the fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A variation, called "field fence," has narrower openings at the bottom and wider openings at the top, which helps prevent animals from putting their feet through the fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] For example, horses in particular are safer when kept inside a woven-wire fence with smaller openings, such as a "no climb" fence with openings no larger than 2 by 4 inches (5.1 by 10.2 cm).
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Hog panels or cattle panels consist of heavy wire approximately 0.25 inches (6 mm) or more in diameter running horizontally and vertically, and welded at the intersections.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The panels, which are sold in lengths of 16 or 8 feet (4.88 or 2.44 m) rather than in rolls, are rigid and self-supporting.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] No corner bracing is needed for panels, as they are not stretched, and there is no tension on the corner posts.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Chain link fencing is occasionally used for some livestock containment.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] However, due to cost, it is not particularly common to fence large areas, where less expensive forms of woven wire are equally suitable.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] When used in small enclosures, it is easily deformed by livestock, resulting in high ongoing maintenance costs.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Electric fencing became widely available in the 1950s and has been used both for temporary fences and to improve the security of fences made of other materials.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] It is most commonly made using lightweight steel wire (usually 14–17 gauge) attached to posts with insulators made of porcelain or plastic.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Synthetic web or rope with thin steel wires interwoven to carry the electrical charge has become popular in recent years, particularly where additional visibility is desired.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A fence charger places an electrical pulse from ground to the wire about once per second.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The pulse is narrow and usually around 5–20 kV.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Animals receive an uncomfortable but harmless shock when they contact the wire and learn to stay away from it.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Synthetic fence encompasses a wide range of products.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Vinyl-coated wire fence is typically made from high-tensile wire.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Some forms are non-electric; others incorporate layers of graphite to conduct current from the wire to the outer surface of the coated product, allowing the product to be electrified.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] It can be of any color, with white particularly common in the United States, so that the fencing is visible to livestock.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Most forms can be installed on either wood posts or steel t-posts.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A variant, sometimes called "vinyl rail" or "strap fencing", consists of two or more vinyl-encased wires, with vinyl or another synthetic material between them, to create a "rail" that is anywhere from 1 to 10 centimetres (3⁄8 to 3+15⁄16 in) wide.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A vinyl fence is installed similarly to a plain high-tensile fence and must be stretched tight.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Strong bracing of posts at corners and in the middle of long fencelines is required.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] As with other wire fences, keeping vinyl fencing tightened regularly is key to safety and appearance.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A mesh form of vinyl fencing without internal wires is marketed as "deer fence" and used in some locations to augment other fencing to keep out wild animals.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Some forms of vinyl fencing resemble vinyl-coated wire fencing but lack an internal wire and are marketed to livestock owners.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] They are marketed as particularly safe, but their strength in containing animals is under debate.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Fences of wood, stranded cable, and pipe are used where cost is less of a consideration, particularly on horse farms, or in pens or corrals where livestock are likely to challenge the fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Synthetic materials with wood-like qualities are also used, though they are the most expensive option in most situations.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] In some areas, these types of fencing materials can be cost-effective if plentiful.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] For example, scrap pipe is often easily obtained at a low price if oil fields are nearby, and wooden rails can sometimes be harvested from the owner's own land if it contains suitable standing timber.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] A cattle grid is an obstacle used to prevent livestock, such as sheep, cattle, pigs, horses, or mules from passing along a road or railway that penetrates the fencing surrounding an enclosed piece of land or border.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] All types of agricultural fencing require regular maintenance to ensure their effectiveness.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Cattle and horses are strong enough to go through most types of fence by main force, and occasionally do so when frightened or motivated by hunger, thirst, or sex drive.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Weather, flood, fire, and damage from vandals or motor vehicle accidents can do similar damage and may allow livestock to escape.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] All types of livestock fencing can be barriers and traps for wildlife, causing injuries and fatalities.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Wildlife can get their legs tangled in barbed wire or woven wire with a strand of barbed wire on top.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Woven wire can barricade animals that cannot jump the fence but are too large to crawl through the holes, such as fawns, bears, and bobcats.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Some wire fences are too difficult for larger, fast-moving birds to see, and they can get entangled in them.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Adding visibility to wire fences can help reduce wildlife collisions.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Reducing the height of woven and strand wire fences to no more than 40 inches (102 cm) can make it easier for wildlife to jump over with less risk of entanglement.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Using barbless wires on top and bottom reduces cuts on wildlife that crawl under strand fences or those that try to climb over.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Fladry lines, made of cloth, metal, or other materials, are sometimes used on fences to discourage wolves from entering a livestock enclosure.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Deer and many goats can easily jump an ordinary agricultural fence, and so special fencing is needed for farming goats or deer, or to keep wild deer out of farmland and gardens.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] Deer fence is often made of lightweight woven wire netting nearly 2 metres (6 feet 7 inches) high on lightweight posts, otherwise made like an ordinary woven wire fence.
[src:electrical-injury/agricultural-fencing] The additional width prevents deer from approaching the fence close enough to jump it.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] The inner ear is particularly important in the maintenance of balance and equilibrium because it contains sensors for both angular (rotational) and linear motion.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Airsickness is usually a combination of spatial disorientation, nausea and vomiting.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Nausea, vomiting, vertigo, loss of appetite, cold sweating, skin pallor, difficulty concentrating, confusion, drowsiness, headache, and increased fatigue.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Severe airsickness may cause a person to become completely incapacitated.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Pilots who are susceptible to airsickness are usually advised not to take anti-motion sickness medications (prescription or over-the-counter).
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] These medications can make one drowsy or affect brain functions in other ways.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] A method to increase pilot resistance to airsickness consists of repetitive exposure to the flying conditions that initially resulted in airsickness.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] In other words, repeated exposure to the flight environment decreases an individual's susceptibility to subsequent airsickness.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] The US Air Force and US Navy have an Air Sickness Management Program and use a device called a Barany chair to desensitize trainees over 3 days.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] This combined with progressive relaxation (diaphragmatic breathing and muscle tensing) yields a high success rate.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] The Italian Air Force also uses a similar spinning chair and psychologic relaxation techniques which yields an 82% long-term success rate, over a 10-day training period.
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Several devices have been introduced that are intended to reduce motion sickness through stimulation of various body parts (usually the wrist).
[src:electrical-injury/airsickness] Alternative treatments include ginger and acupuncture, with variable effectiveness.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is nicknamed the *Yellowhammer State*, after the state bird.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is also known as the "Heart of Dixie" and the "Cotton State".
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state has diverse geography, with the north dominated by the mountainous Tennessee Valley and the south by Mobile Bay.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's capital is Montgomery, and its largest city by population and area is Huntsville.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Its oldest city is Mobile, founded by French colonists (Alabama Creoles) in 1702 as the capital of French Louisiana.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Greater Birmingham is Alabama's largest metropolitan area and its economic center.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Politically, as part of the Deep South, or "Bible Belt", Alabama is a predominantly conservative state and is known for its Southern culture.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Within Alabama, American football, particularly at the college level, is part of the state's culture.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Originally the area of Alabama was home to many native tribes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It was a Spanish territory from the sixteenth century until the French acquired it in the early eighteenth century.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The British won the territory in 1763 until losing it in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Spain held Mobile as part of Spanish West Florida until 1813.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In December 1819, Alabama was recognized as a state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] During the antebellum period, Alabama was a major producer of cotton and widely used African American slave labor.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 1861, the state seceded from the United States to become part of the Confederate States of America, with Montgomery acting as its first capital.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Following the American Civil War, it would suffer decades of economic hardship, in part due to agriculture and a few cash crops being the main driver of the state's economy.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Similar to other former slave states, Alabamian legislators employed Jim Crow laws from the late 19th century until the 1960s.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] High-profile events such as the Selma to Montgomery marches made the state a focal point of the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] During and after World War II, the state's economy diversified with new industries.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 1960, the establishment of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville helped boost Alabama's economic growth by developing a local aerospace industry.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's economy in the 21st century is based on automotive, finance, tourism, manufacturing, aerospace, mineral extraction, healthcare, education, retail, and technology.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Despite the economic and industrial growth in recent decades, Alabama typically ranks low in terms of health outcomes, educational attainment, and median household income.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The name of the Alabama River and state is derived from the Alabama people, a Muskogean-speaking tribe whose members lived just below the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers on the upper reaches of the river.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the Alabama language, the word for a person of Alabama lineage is *Albaamo* (or variously *Albaama* or *Albàamo* in different dialects; the plural form is *Albaamaha*).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The word's spelling varies significantly among historical sources.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The first usage appears in three accounts of the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540: Garcilaso de la Vega used *Alibamo*, while the Knight of Elvas and Rodrigo Ranjel wrote *Alibamu* and *Limamu*, respectively, in transliterations of the term.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] As early as 1702, the French called the tribe the *Alibamon*, with French maps identifying the river as *Rivière des Alibamons*.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Other spellings of the name have included *Alibamu*, *Alabamo*, *Albama*, *Alebamon*, *Alibama*, *Alibamou*, *Alabamu*, and *Allibamou*.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The use of state names derived from Native American languages is common in the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] An estimated 26 states have names of Native American origin.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Some scholars suggest the word comes from the Choctaw *alba* (meaning 'plants' or 'weeds') and *amo* (meaning 'to cut', 'to trim', or 'to gather').
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The meaning may have been 'clearers of the thicket' or 'herb gatherers', referring to clearing land for cultivation or collecting medicinal plants.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state has numerous place names of Native American origin.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] An 1842 article in the *Jacksonville Republican* proposed it meant 'Here We Rest'.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This notion was popularized in the 1850s through the writings of Alexander Beaufort Meek.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Experts in the Muskogean languages have not found any evidence to support such a translation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Indigenous peoples of varying cultures lived in the area for thousands of years before the advent of European colonization.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Trade with the northeastern tribes by the Ohio River began during the Burial Mound Period (1000 BC – 700 AD) and continued until European contact.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The agrarian Mississippian culture covered most of the state from 1000 to 1600 AD, with one of its major polities centered around what is now the Moundville Archaeological Site in Moundville, Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This is the second-largest complex of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in present-day Illinois, which was the earliest center of the culture.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Analysis of artifacts from archaeological excavations at Moundville were the basis of scholars' formulating the characteristics of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the SECC appears to have no direct links to Mesoamerican culture but developed independently.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Ceremonial Complex represents a major component of the religion of the Mississippian peoples; it is one of the primary means by which their religion is understood.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Among the historical tribes of Native American people living in present-day Alabama at the time of European contact were the Cherokee, an Iroquoian language people; and the Muskogean-speaking Alabama (*Alibamu*), Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Koasati.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] While part of the same large language family, the Muskogee tribes developed distinct cultures and languages.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Spanish were the first Europeans to reach Alabama during their exploration of North America in the 16th century.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The expedition of Hernando de Soto passed through Mabila and other parts of the state in 1540.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] More than 160 years later, the French founded the region's first European settlement at Old Mobile in 1702.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The city was moved to the current site of Mobile in 1711.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This area was claimed by the French from 1702 to 1763 as part of La Louisiane.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] After the French lost to the British in the Seven Years' War, it became part of British West Florida from 1763 to 1783.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] After the U.S. victory in the American Revolutionary War, the territory was divided between the United States and Spain.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The latter retained control of this western territory from 1783 until the surrender of the Spanish garrison at Mobile to U.S. forces on April 13, 1813.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Thomas Bassett, a loyalist to the British monarchy during the Revolutionary era, was one of the earliest white settlers in the state outside Mobile.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] He settled in the Tombigbee District during the early 1770s.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The district's boundaries were roughly limited to the area within a few miles of the Tombigbee River and included portions of what is today southern Clarke County, northernmost Mobile County, and most of Washington County.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] What are now Baldwin and Mobile counties became part of Spanish West Florida in 1783, part of the independent Republic of West Florida in 1810, and finally part of the Mississippi Territory in 1812.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Most of what is now the northern two-thirds of Alabama was known as the Yazoo lands beginning during the British colonial period.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It was claimed by the Province of Georgia from 1767 onwards.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, it remained a part of Georgia, although heavily disputed.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] With the exception of the area around Mobile and the Yazoo lands, what is now the lower one-third of Alabama was made part of the Mississippi Territory when it was organized in 1798.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Yazoo lands were added to the territory in 1804, following the Yazoo land scandal.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Spain kept a claim on its former Spanish West Florida territory in what would become the coastal counties until the Adams–Onís Treaty officially ceded it to the U.S. in 1819.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The creation of the Mississippi Territory quickly prompted debates over its division.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Amid pressure from white southerners who sought the establishment of two slave states, Congress formed the Alabama Territory from the eastern half of the Mississippi Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The legislation appointed William Wyatt Bibb of Georgia as the first governor of the newly designated Alabama Territory.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Before Mississippi's admission to statehood on December 10, 1817, the more sparsely settled eastern half of the territory was separated and named the Alabama Territory.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The United States Congress created the Alabama Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Stephens, now abandoned, served as the territorial capital from 1817 to 1819.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama was admitted as the 22nd state on December 14, 1819, with Congress selecting Huntsville as the site for the first Constitutional Convention.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] From July 5 to August 2, 1819, delegates met to prepare the new state constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Huntsville served as temporary capital from 1819 to 1820, when the seat of government moved to Cahaba in Dallas County.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Cahaba, now a ghost town, was the first permanent state capital from 1820 to 1825.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Alabama Fever land rush was underway when the state was admitted to the Union, with settlers and land speculators pouring into the state to take advantage of fertile land suitable for cotton cultivation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Part of the frontier in the 1820s and 1830s, its constitution provided for universal suffrage for white men.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Southeastern planters and traders from the Upper South brought slaves with them as the cotton plantations in Alabama expanded.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The economy of the central Black Belt (named for its dark, productive soil) was built around large cotton plantations whose owners' wealth grew mainly from slave labor.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The area also drew many poor, disenfranchised people who became subsistence farmers.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama had an estimated population of under 10,000 people in 1810, but it increased to more than 300,000 people by 1830.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Most Native American tribes were completely removed from the state within a few years of the passage of the Indian Removal Act by Congress in 1830.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] From 1826 to 1846, Tuscaloosa served as Alabama's capital.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] On January 30, 1846, the Alabama legislature announced it had voted to move the capital city from Tuscaloosa to Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The first legislative session in the new capital met in December 1847.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A new capitol building was erected under the direction of Stephen Decatur Button of Philadelphia.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The first structure burned down in 1849, but was rebuilt on the same site in 1851.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This second capitol building in Montgomery remains to the present day.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It was designed by Barachias Holt of Exeter, Maine.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] By 1860, the population had increased to 964,201 people, of which nearly half, 435,080, were enslaved African Americans, and 2,690 were free people of color.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] On January 11, 1861, Alabama declared its secession from the Union.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] After remaining an independent republic for a few days, it joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Confederacy's capital was initially at Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama was heavily involved in the American Civil War.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Although comparatively few battles were fought in the state, Alabama contributed about 120,000 soldiers to the war effort.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A company of cavalry soldiers from Huntsville, Alabama, joined Nathan Bedford Forrest's battalion in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The company wore new uniforms with yellow trim on the sleeves, collar and coattails.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This led to them being greeted with "Yellowhammer", and the name later was applied to all Alabama troops in the Confederate Army.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's slaves were freed by the 13th Amendment in 1865.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama was under military rule from the end of the war in May 1865 until its official restoration to the Union in 1868.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] From 1867 to 1874, with most white citizens barred temporarily from voting and freedmen enfranchised, many African Americans emerged as political leaders in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama was represented in Congress during this period by three African-American congressmen: Jeremiah Haralson, Benjamin S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Following the war, the state remained chiefly agricultural, with an economy tied to cotton.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] During the Reconstruction era, state legislators ratified a new state constitution in 1868 which created the state's first public school system and expanded women's rights.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Legislators funded numerous public road and railroad projects, although these were plagued with allegations of fraud and misappropriation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Organized insurgent, resistance groups tried to suppress the freedmen and Republicans.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] These groups included The Ku Klux Klan, the Pale Faces, Knights of the White Camellia, Red Shirts, and the White League.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Reconstruction in Alabama ended in 1874, when the Democrats regained control of the legislature and governor's office through an election dominated by fraud and violence.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] They wrote another constitution in 1875, and the legislature passed the Blaine Amendment, prohibiting public money from being used to finance religiously affiliated schools.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The same year, legislation was approved that called for racially segregated schools.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Railroad passenger cars were segregated in 1891.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The 1901 constitution required racial segregation of public schools.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] By 1903 only 2,980 African Americans were registered in Alabama, although at least 74,000 were literate.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This compared to more than 181,000 African Americans eligible to vote in 1900.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The numbers dropped even more in later decades.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state legislature passed additional racial segregation laws related to public facilities into the 1950s: jails were segregated in 1911; hospitals in 1915; toilets, hotels, and restaurants in 1928; and bus stop waiting rooms in 1945.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] While the planter class had persuaded poor whites to vote for this legislative effort to suppress black voting, the new restrictions resulted in their disenfranchisement as well, due mostly to the imposition of a cumulative poll tax.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] By 1941, whites constituted a slight majority of those disenfranchised by these laws: 600,000 whites vs.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Nearly all blacks had lost the ability to vote.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Despite numerous legal challenges which succeeded in overturning certain provisions, the state legislature would create new ones to maintain disenfranchisement.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The exclusion of blacks from the political system persisted until after passage of federal civil rights legislation in 1965 to enforce their constitutional rights as citizens.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The rural-dominated Alabama legislature consistently underfunded schools and services for the disenfranchised African Americans, but it did not relieve them of paying taxes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Partially as a response to chronic underfunding of education for African Americans in the South, the Rosenwald Fund began funding the construction of what came to be known as Rosenwald Schools.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In Alabama, these schools were designed, and the construction partially financed with Rosenwald funds, which paid one-third of the construction costs.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The fund required the local community and state to raise matching funds to pay the rest.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Black residents effectively taxed themselves twice, by raising additional monies to supply matching funds for such schools, which were built in many rural areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] They often donated land and labor as well.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Beginning in 1913, the first 80 Rosenwald Schools were built in Alabama for African American children.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A total of 387 schools, seven teachers' houses, and several vocational buildings were completed by 1937 in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Several of the surviving school buildings in the state are now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Reflecting this emigration, the population growth rate in Alabama (see "historical populations" table below) dropped by nearly half from 1910 to 1920.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] At the same time, many rural people migrated to the city of Birmingham to work in new industrial jobs.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Birmingham experienced such rapid growth it was called the "Magic City".
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] By 1920, Birmingham was the 36th-largest city in the United States.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Heavy industry and mining were the basis of its economy.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Its residents were under-represented for decades in the state legislature, which refused to redistrict after each decennial census according to population changes, as it was required by the state constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This did not change until the late 1960s following a lawsuit and court order.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Industrial development related to the demands of World War II brought a level of prosperity to the state not seen since before the civil war.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Rural workers poured into the largest cities in the state for better jobs and a higher standard of living.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] One example of this massive influx of workers occurred in Mobile.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Between 1940 and 1943, more than 89,000 people moved into the city to work for war-related industries.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Cotton and other cash crops faded in importance as the state developed a manufacturing and service base.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Despite massive population changes in the state from 1901 to 1961, the rural-dominated legislature refused to reapportion House and Senate seats based on population, as required by the state constitution to follow the results of decennial censuses.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] They held on to old representation to maintain political and economic power in agricultural areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] One result was that Jefferson County, containing Birmingham's industrial and economic powerhouse, contributed more than one-third of all tax revenue to the state, but did not receive a proportional amount in services.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Urban interests were consistently underrepresented in the legislature.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the United States Supreme Court cases of *Baker v.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Sims* (1964), the court ruled that the principle of "one man, one vote" needed to be the basis of both houses of state legislatures, and that their districts had to be based on population rather than geographic counties.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] African Americans continued to press in the 1950s and 1960s to end disenfranchisement and segregation in the state through the civil rights movement, including legal challenges.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Board of Education* that public schools had to be desegregated, but Alabama was slow to comply.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] During the 1960s, under Governor George Wallace, Alabama resisted compliance with federal demands for desegregation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The civil rights movement had notable events in Alabama, including the Montgomery bus boycott (1955–1956), Freedom Rides in 1961, and 1965 Selma to Montgomery marches.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] These contributed to Congressional passage and enactment of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 by the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Legal segregation ended in the states in 1964, although Jim Crow customs often continued until specifically challenged in court.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to *The New York Times*, by 2017, many of Alabama's African Americans were living in Alabama's cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Also, the Black Belt region across central Alabama "is home to largely poor counties that are predominantly African-American.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 1972, for the first time since 1901, the legislature completed the congressional redistricting based on the decennial census.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This benefited the urban areas that had developed, as well as all in the population who had been underrepresented for more than sixty years.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Other changes were made to implement representative state house and senate districts.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama has made some changes since the late 20th century and has used new types of voting to increase representation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the 1980s, an omnibus redistricting case, *Dillard v.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Crenshaw County*, challenged the at-large voting for representative seats of 180 Alabama jurisdictions, including counties and school boards.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] At-large voting had diluted the votes of any minority in a county, as the majority tended to take all seats.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Despite African Americans making up a significant minority in the state, they had been unable to elect any representatives in most of the at-large jurisdictions.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] As part of settlement of this case, five Alabama cities and counties, including Chilton County, adopted a system of cumulative voting for election of representatives in multi-seat jurisdictions.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This has resulted in more proportional representation for voters.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In another form of proportional representation, 23 jurisdictions use limited voting, as in Conecuh County.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 1982, limited voting was first tested in Conecuh County.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Together use of these systems has increased the number of African Americans and women being elected to local offices, resulting in governments that are more representative of their citizens.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, the state's economy shifted away from its traditional lumber, steel, and textile industries because of increased foreign competition.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] However, the state, particularly Huntsville, benefited from the opening of the George C.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Marshall Space Flight Center in 1960, a major facility in the development of the Saturn rocket program and the space shuttle.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Technology and manufacturing industries, such as automobile assembly, replaced some of the state's older industries in the late twentieth century, but the state's economy and growth lagged behind other states in the area, such as Georgia and Florida.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2001, Alabama Supreme Court chief justice Roy Moore installed a statue of the Ten Commandments in the capitol in Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Circuit Court ordered the statue removed, but Moore refused to follow the court order, which led to protests around the capitol in favor of keeping the monument.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The monument was removed in August 2003.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A few natural disasters have occurred in the state in the twenty-first century.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2004, Hurricane Ivan, a category 3 storm upon landfall, struck the state and caused over $18 billion of damage.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It was among the most destructive storms to strike the state in its modern history.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A super outbreak of 62 tornadoes hit the state in April 2011 and killed 238 people, devastating many communities.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is the thirtieth-largest state in the United States with 52,419 square miles (135,760 km2) of total area: 3.2% of the area is water, making Alabama 23rd in the amount of surface water, also giving it the second-largest inland waterway system in the United States.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] About three-fifths of the land area is part of the Gulf Coastal Plain, a gentle plain with a general descent towards the Mississippi River and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The North Alabama region is mostly mountainous, with the Tennessee River cutting a large valley and creating numerous creeks, streams, rivers, mountains, and lakes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is bordered by the states of Tennessee to the north, Georgia to the east, Florida to the south, and Mississippi to the west.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama has a coastline on the Gulf of Mexico, in the extreme southern edge of the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state ranges in elevation from sea level at Mobile Bay to more than 2,000 feet (610 m) in the northeast, to Mount Cheaha at 2,413 ft (735 m).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's land consists of 22 million acres (89,000 km2) of forest or 67% of the state's total land area.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Suburban Baldwin County, along the Gulf Coast, is the largest county in the state in both land area and water area.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Additionally, Alabama has four National Forests: Conecuh, Talladega, Tuskegee, and William B.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama also contains the Natchez Trace Parkway, the Selma To Montgomery National Historic Trail, and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A 5-mile (8 km)-wide meteorite impact crater is located in Elmore County, just north of Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This is the Wetumpka crater, the site of "Alabama's greatest natural disaster".
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A 1,000-foot (300 m)-wide meteorite hit the area about 80 million years ago.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2002, Christian Koeberl with the Institute of Geochemistry University of Vienna published evidence and established the site as the 157th recognized impact crater on Earth.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The average annual temperature is 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Temperatures tend to be warmer in the southern part of the state with its proximity to the Gulf of Mexico, while the northern parts of the state, especially in the Appalachian Mountains in the northeast, tend to be slightly cooler.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Generally, Alabama has very hot summers and mild winters with copious precipitation throughout the year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama receives an average of 56 inches (1,400 mm) of rainfall annually and enjoys a lengthy growing season of up to 300 days in the southern part of the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Summers in Alabama are among the hottest in the U.S., with high temperatures averaging over 90 °F (32 °C) throughout the summer in some parts of the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is also prone to tropical storms and hurricanes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Areas of the state far away from the Gulf are not immune to the effects of the storms, which often dump tremendous amounts of rain as they move inland and weaken.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] South Alabama reports many thunderstorms.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Gulf Coast, around Mobile Bay, averages between 70 and 80 days per year with thunder reported.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This activity decreases somewhat further north in the state, but even the far north of the state reports thunder on about 60 days per year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Occasionally, thunderstorms are severe with frequent lightning and large hail; the central and northern parts of the state are most vulnerable to this type of storm.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama ranks ninth in the number of deaths from lightning and tenth in the number of deaths from lightning strikes per capita.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama, along with Oklahoma and Iowa, has the most confirmed F5 and EF5 tornadoes of any state, according to statistics from the National Climatic Data Center for the period January 1, 1950, to June 2013.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Several long-tracked F5/EF5 tornadoes have contributed to Alabama reporting more tornado fatalities since 1950 than any other state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state was affected by the 1974 Super Outbreak and was devastated tremendously by the 2011 Super Outbreak.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The 2011 Super Outbreak produced a record amount of tornadoes in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The peak season for tornadoes varies from the northern to southern parts of the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is one of the few places in the world that has a secondary tornado season in November and December besides the typically severe spring.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The northern part—along the Tennessee River Valley—is most vulnerable.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The area of Alabama and Mississippi most affected by tornadoes is sometimes referred to as Dixie Alley, as distinct from the Tornado Alley of the Southern Plains.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Winters are generally mild in Alabama, as they are throughout most of the Southeastern United States, with average January low temperatures around 40 °F (4 °C) in Mobile and around 32 °F (0 °C) in Birmingham.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Although snow is a rare event in much of Alabama, areas of the state north of Montgomery may receive a dusting of snow a few times every winter, with an occasional moderately heavy snowfall every few years.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Historic snowfall events include New Year's Eve 1963 snowstorm and the 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The annual average snowfall for the Birmingham area is 2 inches (51 mm) per year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the southern Gulf coast, snowfall is less frequent, sometimes going several years without any snowfall.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's highest temperature of 112 °F (44 °C) was recorded on September 5, 1925, in the unincorporated community of Centerville.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The record low of −27 °F (−33 °C) occurred on January 30, 1966, in New Market.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state is usually ranked among the top in nation for its range of overall biodiversity.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is in the subtropical coniferous forest biome and once boasted huge expanses of pine forest, which still form the largest proportion of forests in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It currently ranks fifth in the nation for the diversity of its flora.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It is home to nearly 4,000 pteridophyte and spermatophyte plant species.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Indigenous animal species in the state include 62 mammal species, 93 reptile species, 73 amphibian species, roughly 307 native freshwater fish species, and 420 bird species that spend at least part of their year within the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Invertebrates include 97 crayfish species and 383 mollusk species.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] 113 of these mollusk species have never been collected outside the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the state contains 461 municipalities, consisting of 174 cities and 287 towns.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Covering only 9.6% of Alabama's land mass, its municipalities are home to 60.4% of its population.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Montgomery, the state's capital, is the third-most populous settlement in Alabama; and the most populous city is Huntsville.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the state contains 12 metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama's largest metropolitan area was Greater Birmingham.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] At the 1800 United States census, Alabama had a population of 1,250 people.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Since then, the state has continued to experience population growth with every U.S. census.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to the 2020 United States census the population of Alabama was 5,024,279, which represents an increase of 244,543 or 5.12%, since the 2010 census.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 121,054 (502,457 births minus 381,403 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 104,991 into the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to statistics from 2012, immigration from outside the U.S. resulted in a net increase of 31,180 people, and migration within the country produced a net gain of 73,811 people.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state had 108,000 foreign-born residents (2.4% of the state population), of which an estimated 22.2% were undocumented (24,000).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico, China, India, Germany and Guatemala as of 2018.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,752 homeless people in Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] With a population density of 99.2 people per square mile as of 2020, the majority of the state's population lives in North, Central, and South Alabama, spread throughout the Huntsville, Birmingham, Montgomery and Mobile metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The center of population of Alabama is located in Chilton County, outside the town of Jemison.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Many American Indian tribes such as the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Coushatta inhabited present-day Alabama before European colonization.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] With Spanish, French, and British colonization of Alabama, white and black Americans migrated to the area.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] From European colonization to U.S. statehood, Alabama's population grew to become increasingly non-Hispanic white and African American.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] By the 2020 census, Alabama's total racial and ethnic population was 66.5% non-Hispanic white and 26.9% African American, with a growing Hispanic and Latino population of 5.3%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabamians citing "American" ancestry are of overwhelmingly English extraction.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Demographers estimate that a minimum of 20–23% of people in Alabama are of predominantly English ancestry and state that the figure is probably much higher.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the 1980 census, 1,139,976 people in Alabama cited that they were of English ancestry out of a total state population of 2,824,719 making them 41% of the state at the time and the largest ethnic group.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama has the 5th-highest black and African American population among U.S. states at 25.8% alone as of 2020.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2011, 46.6% of Alabama's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Scots-Irish were the largest non-English immigrant group from the British Isles before the American Revolution, and many settled in the South, later moving into the Deep South as it was developed.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 1984, under the Davis–Strong Act, the state legislature established the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Indigenous groups within the state had increasingly been demanding recognition as ethnic groups and seeking an end to discrimination.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Given the long history of slavery and associated racial segregation, the Native American or American Indian peoples, who have sometimes been of mixed race, have insisted on having their cultural identification respected.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the past, their self-identification was often overlooked as the state tried to impose a binary breakdown of society into white and black.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state has officially recognized nine American Indian tribes in the state, descended mostly from the Five Civilized Tribes of the American Southeast.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The state government has promoted recognition of American Indian contributions to the state, including the designation in 2000 for Columbus Day to be jointly celebrated as American Indian Heritage Day.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2020, 33,625 identified as being Native American alone, and 97,405 did in combination with one or more other races.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey's estimates, approximately 94% of Alabamians speak English as their sole language, while 6% spoke a language other than English.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Of other languages, the majority of its multilingual population speaks Spanish (3.8%).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In a separate 2021 study by the American University Washington College of Law, Spanish was spoken by 156,656 residents.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Following, Korean, Vietnamese, Mandarin and Cantonese, German, French, and Tagalog were the most-spoken languages; among its French-speaking population, the majority have preserved their language since French colonization.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Pre-colonial and present-day Alabamians have adhered to multiple religions including Native American and African diaspora religions, and predominantly Christianity with the establishment of Spanish missions in Florida.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Other faiths including Judaism, Islam, and Indian religions were introduced since European colonization and American settlement.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] According to a 2023 Public Religion Research Institute survey, an estimated 80% of the adult population were Christian.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In the 2008 American Religious Identification Survey, 86% of Alabama respondents reported their religion as Christian, including 6% Catholic, with 11% as having no religion.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The composition of other traditions is 0.5% Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 0.5% Buddhist, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama is located in the middle of the Bible Belt, a region of numerous Protestant Christians.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama has been identified as one of the most religious states in the United States, with about 58% of the population attending church regularly.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A majority of people in the state identify as Evangelical Protestant.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the three largest denominational groups in Alabama are the Southern Baptist Convention, The United Methodist Church, and non-denominational Evangelical Protestant.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In Alabama, the Southern Baptist Convention has the highest number of adherents with 1,380,121; this is followed by the United Methodist Church with 327,734 adherents, non-denominational Evangelical Protestant with 220,938 adherents, and the Catholic Church with 150,647 adherents.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Many Baptist and Methodist congregations became established in the Great Awakening of the early 19th century, when preachers proselytized across the South.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The Assemblies of God had almost 60,000 members, the Churches of Christ had nearly 120,000 members.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In a 2007 survey, nearly 70% of respondents could name all four of the Christian Gospels.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Of those who indicated a religious preference, 59% said they possessed a "full understanding" of their faith and needed no further learning.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In a 2007 poll, 92% of Alabamians reported having at least some confidence in churches in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Although in much smaller numbers, many other religious faiths are represented in the state as well, including Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism, the Baháʼí Faith, and Unitarian Universalism.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Jews have been present in what is now Alabama since 1763, during the colonial era of Mobile, when Sephardic Jews immigrated from London.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The oldest Jewish congregation in the state is Congregation Sha'arai Shomayim in Mobile.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] It was formally recognized by the state legislature on January 25, 1844.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Later immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries tended to be Ashkenazi Jews from eastern Europe.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Jewish denominations in the state include two Orthodox, four Conservative, ten Reform, and one Humanistic synagogue.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Muslims have been increasing in Alabama, with 31 mosques built by 2011, many by African-American converts.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] There are six Dharma centers and organizations for Theravada Buddhists.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Most monastic Buddhist temples are concentrated in southern Mobile County, near Bayou La Batre.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] This area has attracted an influx of refugees from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam during the 1970s and thereafter.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The four temples within a ten-mile radius of Bayou La Batre, include Chua Chanh Giac, Wat Buddharaksa, and Wat Lao Phoutthavihan.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] The first community of adherents of the Baháʼí Faith in Alabama was founded in 1896 by Paul K.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Dealy, who moved from Chicago to Fairhope.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Baháʼí centers in Alabama exist in Birmingham, Huntsville, and Florence.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] In 2018, life expectancy in Alabama was 75.1 years, below the national average of 78.7 years and is the third lowest life expectancy in the country.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Factors that can cause lower life expectancy are maternal mortality, suicide, and gun crimes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] A Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study in 2008 showed that obesity in Alabama is a problem, with most counties having more than 29% of adults obese, except for ten which had a rate between 26% and 29%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Residents of the state, along with those in five other states, were least likely in the nation to be physically active during leisure time.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p01] Alabama, and the southeastern U.S. in general, has one of the highest incidences of adult onset diabetes in the country, exceeding 10% of adults.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, Alabama's total gross state product was $341.1 billion, and the state's per capita personal income was $59,677.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state has invested in aerospace, education, health care, banking, and various heavy industries, including automobile manufacturing, mineral extraction, steel production and fabrication.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] By 2006, crop and animal production in Alabama was valued at $1.5 billion.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In contrast to the primarily agricultural economy of the previous century, this was only about one percent of the state's gross domestic product.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The number of private farms has declined at a steady rate since the 1960s, as land has been sold to developers, timber companies, and large farming conglomerates.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2025, 99.4% of Alabama businesses were small businesses and employed 46.0% of the state's workforce.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 5.8% in April 2015.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] This compared to a nationwide seasonally adjusted rate of 5.4%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] As of May 2025, the unemployment rate was 3.3%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has no minimum wage and in February 2016 passed legislation preventing municipalities from setting one.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] As of 2018, Alabama has the sixth highest poverty rate among states in the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2017, United Nations Special Rapporteur Philip Alston toured parts of rural Alabama and observed environmental conditions that he said were poorer than anywhere he had seen in the developed world.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's agricultural outputs include poultry and eggs, cattle, fish, plant nursery items, peanuts, cotton, grains such as corn and sorghum, vegetables, milk, soybeans, and peaches.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Although known as "The Cotton State", Alabama ranks between eighth and tenth in national cotton production, according to various reports, with Texas, Georgia and Mississippi comprising the top three.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Aquaculture is a large part of the economy of Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabamians began to practice aquaculture in the early 1960s.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] U.S. farm-raised catfish is the 8th most popular seafood product in America.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] By 2008, approximately 4,000 people in Alabama were employed by the catfish industry and Alabama produced 132 million pounds of catfish.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2020, Alabama produced 1⁄3 of the United States' farm-raised catfish.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The total 2020 sales of catfish raised in Alabama equaled $307 million but by 2020 the total employment of Alabamians fell to 2,442.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] From the early 2000s to 2020, the Alabamian catfish industry has declined from 250 farms and 4 processors to 66 farms and 2 processors.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Reasons for this decline include increased feed prices, catfish alternatives, COVID-19's impact on restaurant sales, disease, and fish size.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's industrial outputs include iron and steel products (including cast-iron and steel pipe); paper, lumber, and wood products; mining (mostly coal); plastic products; cars and trucks; and apparel.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In addition, Alabama produces aerospace and electronic products, mostly in the Huntsville area, the location of NASA's George C.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Marshall Space Flight Center and the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Army Materiel Command, headquartered at Redstone Arsenal.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] A great deal of Alabama's economic growth since the 1990s has been due to the state's expanding automotive manufacturing industry.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Located in the state are Honda Manufacturing of Alabama, Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama, Mercedes-Benz U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] International, and Toyota Motor Manufacturing Alabama, as well as their various suppliers.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Since 1993, the automobile industry has generated more than 67,800 new jobs in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama currently ranks 4th in the nation for vehicle exports.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Automakers accounted for approximately a third of the industrial expansion in the state in 2012.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The eight models produced at the state's auto factories totaled combined sales of 74,335 vehicles for 2012.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The strongest model sales during this period were the Hyundai Elantra compact car, the Mercedes-Benz GL-Class sport utility vehicle and the Honda Ridgeline sport utility truck.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Steel producers Outokumpu, Nucor, SSAB, ThyssenKrupp, and U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Steel have facilities in Alabama and employ more than 10,000 people.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In May 2007, German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp selected Calvert in Mobile County for a 4.65 billion combined stainless and carbon steel processing facility.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] ThyssenKrupp's stainless steel division, Inoxum, including the stainless portion of the Calvert plant, was sold to Finnish stainless steel company Outokumpu in 2012.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The remaining portion of the ThyssenKrupp plant had final bids submitted by ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel for $1.6 billion in March 2013.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional submitted a combined bid for the mill at Calvert, plus a majority stake in the ThyssenKrupp mill in Brazil, for $3.8 billion.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In July 2013, the plant was sold to ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Hunt Refining Company, a subsidiary of Hunt Consolidated, Inc., is based in Tuscaloosa and operates a refinery there.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The company also operates terminals in Mobile, Melvin, and Moundville.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] JVC America, Inc. operates an optical disc replication and packaging plant in Tuscaloosa.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company operates a large plant in Gadsden which employs about 1,400 people.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Construction of an Airbus A320 family aircraft assembly plant in Mobile was formally announced by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Center on July 2, 2012.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Brookley Aeroplex for the assembly of the A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Construction began in 2013, with plans for it to become operable by 2015 and produce up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The assembly plant is the company's first factory to be built within the United States.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It was announced on February 1, 2013, that Airbus had hired Alabama-based Hoar Construction to oversee construction of the facility.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The factory officially opened on September 14, 2015, covering one million square feet on 53 acres of flat grassland.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] According to Business Insider, Alabama ranked 14th in most popular states to visit in 2014.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] An estimated 26 million tourists visited the state in 2017 and spent $14.3 billion, providing directly or indirectly 186,900 jobs in the state, which includes 362,000 International tourists spending $589 million.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Mobile is known for having the oldest organized Mardi Gras celebration in the United States, beginning in 1703.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It was also host to the first formally organized Mardi Gras parade in the U.S. in 1830, a tradition that continues to this day.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Mardi Gras is an official state holiday in Mobile and Baldwin counties.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2018, Mobile's Mardi Gras parade was the state's top event, producing the most tourists with an attendance of 892,811.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Space & Rocket Center in Huntsville with an attendance of 849,981, followed by the Birmingham Zoo with 543,090.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Of the parks and natural destinations, Alabama's Gulf Coast topped the list with 6,700,000 visitors.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has historically been a popular region for film shoots due to its diverse landscapes and contrast of environments.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Movies filmed in Alabama include *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, *Get Out*, *42*, *Selma*, *Big Fish*, *The Final Destination*, *Due Date*, and *Need for Speed*.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] UAB Hospital, USA Health University Hospital, Huntsville Hospital, and Children's Hospital of Alabama are the only Level I trauma centers in Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] UAB is the largest state government employer in Alabama, with a workforce of about 18,000.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] A 2017 study found that Alabama had the least competitive health insurance market in the country, with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama having a market share of 84% followed by UnitedHealth Group at 7%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Regions Financial Corporation is the largest bank headquartered in or operating in Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] PNC Financial Services and Wells Fargo also have a major presence in Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Wells Fargo has a regional headquarters, an operations center campus, and a $400 million data center in Birmingham.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Many smaller banks are also headquartered in the Birmingham area, including ServisFirst and New South Federal Savings Bank.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Birmingham also serves as the headquarters for several large investment management companies, including Harbert Management Corporation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Telecommunications provider AT&T, formerly BellSouth, has a major presence in Alabama with several large offices in Birmingham.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Many technology companies are headquartered in Huntsville, such as ADTRAN, a network access company; Intergraph, a computer graphics company; and Avocent, an IT infrastructure company.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Brasfield & Gorrie, BE&K, Hoar Construction, and B.L.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Harbert International, based in Alabama and subsidiaries of URS Corporation, are all routinely are included in the Engineering News-Record lists of top design, international construction, and engineering firms.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The foundational document for Alabama's government is the Alabama Constitution, the current constitution was adopted in 2022.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The former Alabama constitution adopted in 1901 was, with over 850 amendments and almost 87,000 words, by some accounts the world's longest constitution and roughly forty times the length of the United States Constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] There was a significant movement to rewrite and modernize Alabama's constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The former constitution was particularly criticized for its complexity and length intentionally codifying segregation and racism.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's government is divided into three coequal branches.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The legislative branch is the Alabama Legislature, a bicameral assembly composed of the Alabama House of Representatives, with 105 members, and the Alabama Senate, with 35 members.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Legislature is responsible for writing, debating, passing, or defeating state legislation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Republican Party currently holds a majority in both houses of the Legislature.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Legislature has the power to override a gubernatorial veto by a simple majority (most state Legislatures require a two-thirds majority to override a veto).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Until 1964, the state elected state senators on a geographic basis by county, with one per county.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It had not redistricted congressional districts since passage of its constitution in 1901; as a result, urbanized areas were grossly underrepresented.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It had not changed legislative districts to reflect the decennial censuses, either.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] At that time, Alabama and many other states had to change their legislative districting, as many across the country had systems that underrepresented urban areas and districts.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] This had caused decades of underinvestment in such areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] For instance, Birmingham and Jefferson County taxes had supplied one-third of the state budget, but Jefferson County received only 1/67th of state services in funding.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Through the legislative delegations, the Alabama legislature kept control of county governments.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The executive branch is responsible for the execution and oversight of laws.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It is headed by the governor of Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Other members of the executive branch include the cabinet, the lieutenant governor of Alabama, the Attorney General of Alabama, the Alabama Secretary of State, the Alabama State Treasurer, and the State Auditor of Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The current governor is Republican Kay Ivey.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The members of the Legislature take office immediately after the November elections.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Statewide officials, such as the governor, lieutenant governor, attorney general, and other constitutional officers, take office the following January.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The judiciary is responsible for interpreting the Constitution of Alabama and applying the law in state criminal and civil cases.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state's highest court is the Supreme Court of Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama uses partisan elections to select judges.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Since the 1980s judicial campaigns have become increasingly politicized.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The current chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court is Republican Tom Parker.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] All sitting justices on the Alabama Supreme Court are members of the Republican Party.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] There are two intermediate appellate courts, the Court of Civil Appeals and the Court of Criminal Appeals, and four trial courts: the circuit court (trial court of general jurisdiction), and the district, probate, and municipal courts.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has the death penalty with authorized methods of execution that include the electric chair and the gas chamber.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Some critics believe the election of judges has contributed to an exceedingly high rate of executions.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has the highest per capita death penalty rate in the country.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In some years, it imposes more death sentences than does Texas, a state which has a population five times larger.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] However, executions per capita are significantly higher in Texas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Some of its cases have been highly controversial; the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Supreme Court has overturned 83 convictions in death penalty cases.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It was the only state to allow judges to override jury decisions in whether or not to use a death sentence; in 10 cases judges overturned sentences of life imprisonment without parole that were voted unanimously by juries.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] This judicial authority was removed in April 2017.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] On May 14, 2019, Alabama passed the Human Life Protection Act, banning abortion at any stage of pregnancy unless there is a "serious health risk", with no exceptions for rape and incest.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The law subjects doctors who perform abortions with 10 to 99 years imprisonment.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The law was originally supposed to take effect the following November, but on October 29, 2019, U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] District Judge Myron Thompson blocked the law from taking effect due to it being in conflict with the 1973 U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Judge Thompson lifted the injunction, allowing the law to go into effect.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama is one of five to not operate a state lottery and one of just two states, the other being Utah, that prohibits the creation of state lotteries in their constitutions.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Taxes are collected by the Alabama Department of Revenue.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama levies a 2%, 4%, or 5% personal income tax, depending on the amount earned and filing status.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Taxpayers are allowed to deduct their federal income tax from their Alabama state tax, even if taking the standard deduction; those who itemize can also deduct FICA (the Social Security and Medicare tax).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state's general sales tax rate is 4%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Sales tax rates for cities and counties are also added to purchases.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] For example, the total sales tax rate in Mobile County is 10% and there is an additional restaurant tax of 1%, which means a diner in Mobile County would pay an 11% tax on a meal.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2020, sales and excise taxes in Alabama accounted for 38% of all state and local revenue.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama gradually reduced the grocery tax to 2% between 2024 and 2025.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In April 2026, Alabama paused the grocery tax for the months of May and July of that year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The corporate income tax rate in Alabama is 6.5%.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The overall federal, state, and local tax burden in Alabama ranks the state as the second least tax-burdened state in the country.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Property taxes of 0.40% of assessed value per year, are the second-lowest in the U.S., after Hawaii.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state constitution currently requires a voter referendum to raise property taxes.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Historically, an Alabama excise tax "on the storage, use or other consumption in this state of tangible personal property purchased at retail for storage, use or other consumption in this state" was the focus of a 1941 U S Supreme Court ruling, *Curry v United States*.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Each county has its own elected legislative branch, usually called the county commission.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It also has limited executive authority in the county.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Because of the constraints of the Alabama Constitution, which centralizes power in the state legislature, only seven counties (Jefferson, Lee, Mobile, Madison, Montgomery, Shelby, and Tuscaloosa) in the state have limited home rule.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Instead, most counties in the state must lobby the Local Legislation Committee of the state legislature to get simple local policies approved, ranging from waste disposal to land use zoning.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state legislature has retained power over local governments by refusing to pass a constitutional amendment establishing home rule for counties, as recommended by the 1973 Alabama Constitutional Commission.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Legislative delegations retain certain powers over each county.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] United States Supreme Court decisions in *Baker v.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Carr* (1964) required that both houses have districts established on the basis of population, and redistricted after each census, to implement the principle of "one man, one vote".
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Before that, each county was represented by one state senator, leading to under-representation in the state senate for more urbanized, populous counties.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The rural bias of the state legislature, which had also failed to redistrict seats in the state house, affected politics well into the 20th century, failing to recognize the rise of industrial cities and urbanized areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] "The lack of home rule for counties in Alabama has resulted in the proliferation of local legislation permitting counties to do things not authorized by the state constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's constitution has been amended more than 700 times, and almost one-third of the amendments are local in nature, applying to only one county or city.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama is an alcoholic beverage control state, meaning the state government holds a monopoly on the sale of alcohol.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Alabama Alcoholic Beverage Control Board controls the sale and distribution of alcoholic beverages in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] A total of 25 of the 67 counties are "dry counties" which ban the sale of alcohol, and there are many dry municipalities in counties which permit alcohol sales.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] During Reconstruction following the American Civil War, Alabama was occupied by federal troops of the Third Military District under General John Pope.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 1874, the political coalition of white Democrats known as the Redeemers took control of the state government from the Republicans, in part by suppressing the black vote through violence, fraud, and intimidation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] After 1890, a coalition of White Democratic politicians passed laws to segregate and disenfranchise African American residents, a process completed in provisions of the 1901 constitution.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Provisions which disenfranchised blacks resulted in excluding many poor Whites.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] By 1941 more Whites than Blacks had been disenfranchised: 600,000 to 520,000.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The total effects were greater on the black community, as almost all its citizens were disfranchised and relegated to separate and unequal treatment under the law.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] From 1901 through the 1960s, the state did not redraw election districts as population grew and shifted within the state during urbanization and industrialization of certain areas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] As counties were the basis of election districts, the result was a rural minority that dominated state politics through nearly three-quarters of the century, until a series of federal court cases required redistricting in 1972 to meet equal representation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama state politics gained nationwide and international attention in the 1950s and 1960s during the civil rights movement, when whites bureaucratically, and at times violently, resisted protests for electoral and social reform.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Governor George Wallace, the state's only four-term governor, was a controversial figure who vowed to maintain segregation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Only after passage of the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 did African Americans regain the ability to exercise suffrage, among other civil rights.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In many jurisdictions, they continued to be excluded from representation by at-large electoral systems, which allowed the majority of the population to dominate elections.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Some changes at the county level have occurred following court challenges to establish single-member districts that enable a more diverse representation among county boards.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2007, the Alabama Legislature passed, and Republican governor Bob Riley signed a resolution expressing "profound regret" over slavery and its lingering impact.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In a symbolic ceremony, the bill was signed in the Alabama State Capitol, which housed Congress of the Confederate States of America.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans won control of both houses of the legislature for the first time in 136 years.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] As of February 2023, there are a total of 3,707,233 registered voters, with 3,318,679 active, and the others inactive in the state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The 2023 *American Values Atlas* by Public Religion Research Institute found that a majority of Alabama residents support same-sex marriage.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] With the disfranchisement of Blacks in 1901, the state became part of the "Solid South", a system in which the Democratic Party operated as effectively the only viable political party in every Southern state.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] For nearly a hundred years local and state elections in Alabama were decided in the Democratic Party primary, with generally only token Republican challengers running in the general election.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Since the mid- to late 20th century, however, white conservatives started shifting to the Republican Party.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In Alabama, majority-white districts are now expected to regularly elect Republican candidates to federal, state and local office.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Members of the nine seats on the Supreme Court of Alabama and all ten seats on the state appellate courts are elected to office.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Until 1994, no Republicans held any of the court seats.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In that general election, the then-incumbent chief justice, Ernest C.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Hornsby, refused to leave office after losing the election by approximately 3,000 votes to Republican Perry O.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Hornsby sued Alabama and defiantly remained in office for nearly a year before finally giving up the seat after losing in court.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Democrats lost the last of the nineteen court seats in August 2011 with the resignation of the last Democrat on the bench.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In the early 21st century, Republicans hold all seven of the statewide elected executive branch offices.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Republicans hold six of the eight elected seats on the Alabama State Board of Education.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans took large majorities of both chambers of the state legislature, giving them control of that body for the first time in 136 years.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The last remaining statewide Democrat, who served on the Alabama Public Service Commission, was defeated in 2012.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Only three Republican lieutenant governors have been elected since the end of Reconstruction, when Republicans generally represented Reconstruction government, including the newly emancipated freedmen who had gained the franchise.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The three GOP lieutenant governors are Steve Windom (1999–2003), Kay Ivey (2011–2017), and Will Ainsworth (2019–present).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Many metropolitan and suburban counties have voters who are majority Democrats, resulting in local elections being decided in the Democratic primary.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Similarly, most rural counties are majority-Republican and elections are effectively decided in the Republican primary.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] However, since local governments in Alabama are weaker than in other parts of the country, Republicans have the upper hand in government.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's 67 county sheriffs are elected in partisan, at-large races, and Republicans retain the vast majority of those posts.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The current split is 18 Democrats, and 49 Republicans as of 2023.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] However, most of the Democratic sheriffs preside over urban and more populated counties.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The majority of Republican sheriffs have been elected in the more rural counties with lower population.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] As of 2025, the state of Alabama has 11 African-American sheriffs.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state's two U.S. senators are Katie Britt and Tommy Tuberville, both of whom are Republican.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] House of Representatives, the state is represented by seven members, five of whom are Republicans (Mike Rogers, Robert Aderholt, Dale Strong, Barry Moore, and Gary Palmer) and two Democrats (Terri Sewell and Shomari Figures).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Public primary and secondary education in Alabama is under the purview of the Alabama State Board of Education as well as local oversight by 67 county school boards and 60 city boards of education.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Together, 1,496 individual schools provide education for 744,637 elementary and secondary students.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Public school funding is appropriated through the Alabama Legislature through the Education Trust Fund.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] That represented an increase of $444,736,387 over the previous fiscal year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2007, more than 82 percent of schools made Adequate Yearly Progress (AYP) toward student proficiency under the National No Child Left Behind law, using measures determined by the state of Alabama.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] While Alabama's public education system has improved in recent decades, it lags behind in achievement compared to other states.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Census data (2000), Alabama's high school graduation rate (75%) is the fourth lowest in the U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] (after Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The largest educational gains were among people with some college education but without degrees.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] According to National Assessment of Educational Progress (NEAP), Alabama ranks 39 in reading and 40 in math among fourth-grade students in the rankings from 2022.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Generally prohibited in the West at large, school corporal punishment is not unusual in Alabama, with 27,260 public school students paddled at least one time, according to government data for the 2011–2012 school year.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The rate of school corporal punishment in Alabama is surpassed by only Mississippi and Arkansas.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama's programs of higher education include 14 four-year public universities, two-year community colleges, and 17 private, undergraduate and graduate universities.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Public, post-secondary education in Alabama is overseen by the Alabama Commission on Higher Education and the Alabama Department of Postsecondary Education.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Colleges and universities in Alabama offer degree programs from two-year associate degrees to a multitude of doctoral level programs.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The largest single campus in Alabama is Tuskegee University with 5000 acres.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The largest student body is the University of Alabama, located in Tuscaloosa, with 42,360 students enrolled for fall 2025.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Troy University was the largest institution in the state in 2010, with an enrollment of 29,689 students across four Alabama campuses (Troy, Dothan, Montgomery, and Phenix City), as well as sixty learning sites in seventeen other states and eleven other countries.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The oldest institutions are the public University of North Alabama in Florence and the Catholic Church-affiliated Spring Hill College in Mobile, both founded in 1830.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had three universities ranked in the top 100 Public Schools in America (Auburn University at 47, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB) at 76, and University of Alabama at 91).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had four tier one universities (Auburn University, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB), University of Alabama and University of Alabama in Huntsville).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Major newspapers include *Birmingham News*, Mobile *Press-Register*, and *Montgomery Advertiser*.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama literature is characterized by themes of race and issues of gender and war, and is influenced by events such as the American Civil War, the Reconstruction era, the civil rights movement, and the Vietnam War.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Some notable examples of Alabama literature include Harper Lee's *To Kill a Mockingbird*, Winston Groom's *Forrest Gump*, Fannie Flagg's *Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe*, and the biographies of Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has several professional and semi-professional sports teams, including three minor league baseball teams.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Talladega Superspeedway motorsports complex hosts a series of NASCAR events.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] It has a seating capacity of 143,000 and is the thirteenth largest stadium in the world and sixth largest stadium in America.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Also, the Barber Motorsports Park has hosted IndyCar Series and Rolex Sports Car Series races.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The ATP Birmingham was a World Championship Tennis tournament held from 1973 to 1980.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama has hosted several professional golf tournaments, such as the 1984 and 1990 PGA Championship at Shoal Creek, the Barbasol Championship (PGA Tour), the Mobile LPGA Tournament of Champions, Airbus LPGA Classic, and Yokohama Tire LPGA Classic (LPGA Tour), and The Tradition (Champions Tour).
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] College football is extremely popular in Alabama, particularly the University of Alabama Crimson Tide and Auburn University Tigers, rivals in the Southeastern Conference.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Alabama averages over 100,000 fans per game and Auburn averages over 80,000—both numbers among the top twenty in the nation.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Bryant–Denny Stadium is the home of the Alabama football team, and has a seating capacity of 101,821, and is the fifth largest stadium in America.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Jordan-Hare Stadium is the home field of the Auburn football team and seats up to 87,451.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Protective Stadium is home of the UAB Blazers football program and the Birmingham Bowl.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Opening in 2020, Hancock Whitney Stadium in Mobile is the home of the University of South Alabama football team, and serves as the home of the Reese's Senior Bowl, the AHSAA North/South All-star Game, and the LendingTree Bowl; the stadium seats 25,450.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In 2009, Bryant–Denny Stadium and Jordan-Hare Stadium became the homes of the Alabama High School Athletic Association state football championship games, after previously being held at Legion Field in Birmingham.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] For rail transport, Amtrak schedules the *Crescent*, a daily passenger train, running from New York to New Orleans with station stops at Anniston, Birmingham, and Tuscaloosa.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The *Mardi Gras Service* operates daily between Mobile and New Orleans; the Mobile terminus is its only Alabama stop.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] I-22 enters the state from Mississippi and connects Birmingham with Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] In addition, there are currently five auxiliary interstate routes in the state: I-165 in Mobile, I-359 in Tuscaloosa, I-459 around Birmingham, I-565 in Decatur and Huntsville, and I-759 in Gadsden.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] A sixth route, I-685, will be formed when I-85 is rerouted along a new southern bypass of Montgomery.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] A proposed northern bypass of Birmingham will be designated as I-422.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Since a direct connection from I-22 to I-422 will not be possible, I-222 has been proposed, as well.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] Highways also pass through the state, such as U.S.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] There are four toll roads in the state: Montgomery Expressway in Montgomery; Northport/Tuscaloosa Western Bypass in Tuscaloosa and Northport; Emerald Mountain Expressway in Wetumpka; and Beach Express in Orange Beach.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile, Alabama's only saltwater port, is a large seaport on the Gulf of Mexico with inland waterway access to the Midwest by way of the Tennessee–Tombigbee Waterway.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile was ranked 12th by tons of traffic in the United States during 2009.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The newly expanded container terminal at the Port of Mobile was ranked as the 25th busiest for container traffic in the nation during 2011.
[src:electrical-injury/alabama-p02] The state's other ports are on rivers with access to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] An **electrical injury** (**electric injury**) or **electrical shock** (**electric shock**) is damage sustained to the skin or internal organs on direct contact with an electric current.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The injury depends on the density of the current, tissue resistance and duration of contact.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Very small currents may be imperceptible or only produce a light tingling sensation.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] However, a shock caused by low and otherwise harmless current could startle an individual and cause injury due to jerking away or falling.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] A strong electric shock can often cause painful muscle spasms severe enough to dislocate joints or even to break bones.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The loss of muscle control is the reason that a person may be unable to release themselves from the electrical source; if this happens at a height as on a power line they can be thrown off.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Larger currents can result in tissue damage and may trigger ventricular fibrillation or cardiac arrest.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If death results from an electric shock the cause of death is generally referred to as electrocution.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electric injury occurs upon contact of a body part with electricity that causes a sufficient current to pass through the person's tissues.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Contact with energized wiring or devices is the most common cause.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] In cases of exposure to high voltages, such as on a power transmission tower, direct contact may not be necessary as the voltage may "jump" the air gap to the electrical device.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Following an electrical injury from household current, if a person has no symptoms, no underlying heart problems, and is not pregnant, further testing is not required.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Otherwise an electrocardiogram, blood work to check the heart, and urine testing for signs of muscle breakdown may be performed.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Management may involve resuscitation, pain medications, wound management, and heart rhythm monitoring.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electrical injuries affect more than 30,000 people a year in the United States and result in about 1,000 deaths.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Heating due to resistance can cause extensive and deep burns.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] When applied to the hand, electricity can cause involuntary muscle contraction, preventing the victim from untensing their hand muscles and releasing the wire, increasing the risk for serious burns.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Voltage levels of 500 to 1000 volts tend to cause internal burns due to the large energy (which is proportional to the duration multiplied by the square of the voltage divided by resistance or the square of the current multiplied by the resistance) available from the source.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Damage due to current is through tissue heating and/or electroporation injury.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] For most cases of high-energy electrical trauma, the Joule heating in the deeper tissues along the extremity will reach damaging temperatures in a few seconds.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] A domestic power supply voltage (110 or 230 V), 50 or 60 Hz alternating current (AC) through the chest for a duration longer than one second may induce ventricular fibrillation at currents as low as 30 milliamperes (mA).
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] With direct current (DC), 90 to 130 mA are required at the same duration.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If the current has a direct pathway to the heart (e.g., via a cardiac catheter or other kind of electrode), a much lower current of less than 1 mA (AC or DC) can cause fibrillation.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If not immediately treated by defibrillation, ventricular fibrillation is usually lethal, causing cardiac arrest, because all of the heart muscle fibres move independently instead of in the coordinated action needed for successful cardiac cycle to pump blood and maintain circulation.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Short single DC pulses induce VF dependent on the amount of charge (in mC) transferred to the body, which makes the amplitude of the electrical stimulus independent of the exact amount of current flowing through the body for very short pulse durations.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] DC shocks of short duration are usually better tolerated by the heart even at high currents and rarely induce ventricular fibrillation compared to lower currents with longer duration with both DC or AC.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The amount of current can easily reach very high values as amperage is only of second order importance to fibrillation risk in the case of ultra short contact times with direct currents.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] But even if the charge itself is harmless, the amount of energy being discharged still can lead to thermal and chemical hazards if its value is high enough.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] One example of high current electric shock which may be usually harmless is an electrostatic discharge as experienced in everyday life on door handles, car doors etc.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] These currents can reach values up to 60 A without harmful effects on the heart as the duration is in the order of only several ns.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Another example for dangerous electrostatic discharges even without flowing directly through the body are lightning strikes and high voltage arcs.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electric shock which does not lead to death has been shown to cause neuropathy in some cases at the site where the current entered the body.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The neurologic symptoms of electrical injury may occur immediately, which traditionally have a higher likelihood for healing, though they may also be delayed by days to years.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The delayed neurologic consequences of electrical injury have a worse prognosis.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] When the path of electric current proceeds through the head, it appears that, with sufficient current applied, loss of consciousness almost always occurs swiftly.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] This is borne out by research from the field of animal husbandry, where electric stunning has been extensively studied.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If ventricular fibrillation occurs (as above), the blood supply to the brain is diminished, which may cause cerebral hypoxia (and its associated neurologic consequences).
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] There are a variety of psychiatric effects that may occur as a result of electrical injuries.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Behavioral changes can occur as well, even if the path of electric current did not proceed through the head.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] OSHA found that up to 80 percent of its electrical injuries involve thermal burns due to arcing faults.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The arc flash in an electrical fault produces the same type of light radiation from which electric welders protect themselves using face shields with dark glass, heavy leather gloves, and full-coverage clothing.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The heat produced may cause severe burns, especially on unprotected flesh.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The arc blast produced by vaporizing metallic components can break bones and damage internal organs.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The degree of hazard present at a particular location can be determined by a detailed analysis of the electrical system, and appropriate protection worn if the electrical work must be performed with the electricity on.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The minimum current a human can feel depends on the current type (AC or DC) as well as frequency for AC.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] A person can sense electric current as low as 1 mA (rms) for 60 Hz AC and as low as 5 mA for DC.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] At around 10 mA, AC current passing through the arm of a 68-kilogram (150 lb) human can cause powerful muscle contractions; the victim is unable to voluntarily control muscles and cannot release an electrified object.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] This is known as the "let go threshold" and is a criterion for shock hazard in electrical regulations.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The current may, if it is high enough, cause tissue damage or fibrillation which can cause cardiac arrest; more than 30 mA of AC (rms, 60 Hz) or 300–500 mA of DC at high voltage can cause fibrillation.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] A sustained electric shock from AC at 120 V, 60 Hz is an especially dangerous source of ventricular fibrillation because it usually exceeds the let-go threshold, while not delivering enough initial energy to propel the person away from the source.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] However, the potential seriousness of the shock depends on paths through the body that the currents take.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If the voltage is less than 200 V, then the human skin, more precisely the stratum corneum, is the main contributor to the impedance of the body in the case of a macroshock—the passing of current between two contact points on the skin.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The characteristics of the skin are non-linear however.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If the voltage is above 450–600 V, then dielectric breakdown of the skin occurs.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The protection offered by the skin is lowered by perspiration, and this is accelerated if electricity causes muscles to contract above the let-go threshold for a sustained period of time.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] If an electrical circuit is established by electrodes introduced in the body, bypassing the skin, then the potential for lethality is much higher if a circuit through the heart is established.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Currents of only 10 μA can be sufficient to cause fibrillation in this case with a probability of 0.2%.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The voltage necessary for electrocution depends on the current through the body and the duration of the current.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Ohm's law states that the current drawn depends on the resistance of the body.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The resistance of human skin varies from person to person and fluctuates between different times of day.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The NIOSH states "Under dry conditions, the resistance offered by the human body may be as high as 100,000 ohms.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Wet or broken skin may drop the body's resistance to 1,000 ohms," adding that "high-voltage electrical energy quickly breaks down human skin, reducing the human body's resistance to 500 ohms".
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The voltage-current characteristic of human skin is non-linear and depends on many factors such as intensity, duration, history, and frequency of the electrical stimulus.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Sweat gland activity, temperature, and individual variation also influence the voltage-current characteristic of skin.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] In addition to non-linearity, skin impedance exhibits asymmetric and time varying properties.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] These properties can be modeled with reasonable accuracy.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Resistance measurements made at low voltage using a standard ohmmeter do not accurately represent the impedance of human skin over a significant range of conditions.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] For sinusoidal electrical stimulation less than 10 volts, the skin voltage-current characteristic is quasilinear.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Over time, electrical characteristics can become non-linear.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The time required varies from seconds to minutes, depending on stimulus, electrode placement, and individual characteristics.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Between 10 volts and about 30 volts, skin exhibits non-linear but symmetric electrical characteristics.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Above 20 volts, electrical characteristics are both non-linear and symmetric.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Skin conductance can increase by several orders of magnitude in milliseconds.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] This should not be confused with dielectric breakdown, which occurs at hundreds of volts.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] For these reasons, current flow cannot be accurately calculated by simply applying Ohm's law using a fixed resistance model.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The earliest usage of the term "electrocution" cited by the Oxford English Dictionary was an 1889 newspaper reference to the method of execution then being considered.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Shortly thereafter, in 1892, the term was used in *Science* to refer generically to death or injury caused by electricity.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Other issues affecting lethality are frequency, which is an issue in causing cardiac arrest or muscular spasms.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Very high frequency electric current causes tissue burning, but does not stimulate the nerves strongly enough to cause cardiac arrest (see electrosurgery).
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Also important is the pathway: if the current passes through the chest or head, there is an increased chance of death.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Another factor is that cardiac tissue has a chronaxie (response time) of about 3 milliseconds, so electricity at frequencies of higher than about 333 Hz requires more current to cause fibrillation than is required at lower frequencies.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The comparison between the dangers of alternating current at typical power transmission frequencies (i.e., 50 or 60 Hz), and direct current has been a subject of debate ever since the war of the currents in the 1880s.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] It is sometimes suggested that human lethality is most common with alternating current at 100–250 volts; however, death has occurred below this range, with supplies as low as 42 volts.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Assuming a steady current flow (as opposed to a shock from a capacitor or from static electricity), shocks above 2,700 volts are often fatal, with those above 11,000 volts being usually fatal, though exceptional cases have been noted.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] According to the Guinness Book of World Records, seventeen-year-old Brian Latasa survived a 230,000 volt shock on the tower of an ultra-high voltage line in Griffith Park, Los Angeles on November 9, 1967.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] A news report of the event stated that he was "jolted through the air, and landed across the line", and though rescued by firemen, he sustained burns over 40% of his body and was completely paralyzed except for his eyelids.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The shock with the highest voltage reported survived was that of Harry F.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] McGrew, who came in contact with a 340,000 volt transmission line in Huntington Canyon, Utah.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The severity and lethality of electric shocks generally depend on the duration and the amount of current passing through the human body.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Frequency plays a role with AC and pulse DC.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] For example, a high frequency current has a higher ventricular fibrillation threshold than lower frequency.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Also, shorter single pulses have higher thresholds than short pulses.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Below 10 ms are usually believed to have a primarily charge dependent threshold and shock amplitude.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Research shows that for very short electric pulse durations below 100 μs the threshold curve converges into a constant charge criterion independent of peak current or RMS values.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Even though the for both muscle and nerve stimulation including the heart and the brain.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Heating is primarily determined by the amount of energy and is not related to stimulation.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] These definitions have been included into the IEC standard 60479-2 in opposite to IEC 60479-1 which addresses longer pulse durations above 10 ms for both DC and AC, which use a current over time duration curve based classification.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] These principles are used to determine the risks from capacitors, electric weapons, electric fences and other short pulsed low- and high-voltage electrical applications outside the medical field.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Prevention of electrical injuries is one of the fundamental objectives of national electrical codes for permanently-installed electrical systems in buildings.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Shock danger may be reduced by use of an extra-low voltage electrical system that is unlikely to expose a human to dangerous levels of current.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Special isolated power systems may be used in applications such as operating theatres, where electrical equipment must be used in proximity to a person unusually vulnerable to electrical shock.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] For electrical equipment used outdoors or in wet areas, an Earth-leakage circuit breaker known as a residual-current device or *ground fault circuit interrupter*, may provide protection from electrical current leakage.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electrical devices have non-conductive insulation preventing contact with energized wires or parts, or may have conductive metal enclosures connected to earth ground so that users will not be exposed to dangerous voltage.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Double insulated devices have a separate insulation system, distinct from the insulation required for the function of the device, and intended for protection of the user from electrical shock.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] People and animals can be protected by installing electrical equipment out of reach of passers-by, such as on electrical transmission towers, or by installation in an electrical room only accessible to authorized persons.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Stray current leakage or electrical fault current may be diverted by bonding all conductive equipment enclosures together and to the earth.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Current passing through the earth may also provide a hazard of electrical shock, so a ground grid may be installed around installations such as electrical substations.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Lightning protection systems are primarily installed to reduce property damage by lightning strikes, but may not entirely prevent electrical shock hazards.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Persons outdoors during a lightning storm may be advised to take precautions to avoid electrical shock.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Where installation, or maintenance of electrical equipment is required, interlock devices may be used to ensure that all electrical sources are removed from the equipment before accessing normally energized parts.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Administrative procedures such as lockout–tagout are used to protect workers from accidentally re-energizing equipment under repair.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] With proper training and equipment, live-line maintenance is routinely safely carried out on electrical transmission lines energized at hundreds of thousands of volts.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] There were 550 reported electrocution deaths in the US in 1993, 2.1 deaths per million inhabitants.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] At that time, the incidence of electrocutions was decreasing.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electrocutions in the workplace make up the majority of these fatalities.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] From 1980–1992, an average of 411 workers were killed each year by electrocution.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Workplace deaths caused by exposure to electricity in the U.S. increased by nearly 24% between 2015 and 2019, from 134 to 166.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] However, workplace electrical injuries dropped 23% between 2015 and 2019 from 2,480 to 1,900.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] In Sweden, Denmark, Finland and Norway the number of electric deaths per million inhabitants was 0.6, 0.3, 0.3 and 0.2, respectively, in the years 2007–2011.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] In Nigeria, analysis of Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission data found 126 recorded electrocution deaths and 68 serious injuries in 2020 and the first half of 2021.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] People who survive electrical trauma may develop a host of injuries including loss of consciousness, seizures, aphasia, visual disturbances, headaches, tinnitus, paresis, and memory disturbances.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Even without visible burns, electric shock survivors may be faced with long-term muscular pain and discomfort, exhaustion, headache, problems with peripheral nerve conduction and sensation, inadequate balance and coordination, among other symptoms.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electrical injury can lead to problems with neurocognitive function, affecting speed of mental processing, attention, concentration, and memory.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The high frequency of psychological problems is well established and may be multifactorial.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] As with any traumatic and life-threatening experience, electrical injury may result in post traumatic psychiatric disorders.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] There exist several non-profit research institutes that coordinate rehabilitation strategies for electrical injury survivors by connecting them with clinicians that specialize in diagnosis and treatment of various traumas that arise as a result of electrical injury..
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Survivors with persistent neurological, neuropsychological, or functional impairments may require coordinated, multidisciplinary evaluation and rehabilitation strategies, which are sometimes facilitated through specialized research and rehabilitation programs focused on electrical injury.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Specialized rehabilitation programs for electrical injury survivors have been discussed in occupational safety literature.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Mild electric shocks are also used for entertainment, especially as a practical joke for example in such devices as a shocking pen or a shocking gum.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] However devices such as a joy buzzer and most other machines in amusement parks today only use vibration that feels somewhat like an electric shock to someone not expecting it.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electroshock weapons are incapacitant weapons used for subduing a person by administering electric shock to disrupt superficial muscle functions.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] One type is a conductive energy device (CED), an electroshock gun popularly known by the brand name "Taser", which fires projectiles that administer the shock through a thin, flexible wire.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Although they are illegal for personal use in many jurisdictions, Tasers have been marketed to the general public.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Other electroshock weapons such as stun guns, stun batons ("cattle prods"), and electroshock belts administer an electric shock by direct contact.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electric fences are barriers that use electric shocks to deter animals or people from crossing a boundary.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The voltage of the shock may have effects ranging from uncomfortable, to painful or even lethal.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Most electric fencing is used today for agricultural fencing and other forms of animal control purposes, though it is frequently used to enhance security of restricted areas, and there exist places where lethal voltages are used.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Several deliberate uses of electric shock are considered torture.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The Tucker Telephone is a torture device that was used in the Tucker State Prison Farm, Arkansas, whereby the received voltage and current could be controlled with precision, thus causing pain and fear while avoiding visible damage to the victim's body.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electrical torture has been used in war and by repressive regimes since the 1930s.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] During the Algerian War electrical torture was used by French military forces.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Amnesty International published a statement that Russian military forces in Chechnya tortured local women with electric shocks by attaching wires onto their breasts.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The use of electric shocks to torture political prisoners of the Brazilian military dictatorship (1964 - 1985) is detailed in the final report of the National Truth Commission, published December 10, 2014.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The *parrilla* (Spanish for 'grill') is a method of torture whereby the victim is strapped to a metal frame and subjected to electric shock.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] It has been used in a number of contexts in South America.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The *parrilla* was commonly used at Villa Grimaldi, a prison complex maintained by Dirección de Inteligencia Nacional, a part of the Pinochet regime.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] In the 1970s, during the Dirty War, the parrilla was used in Argentina.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Francisco Tenório Júnior (known as Tenorinho), a Brazilian piano player, was subjected to the parrilla during the military dictatorship in Brazil.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The Islamic State has used electric shocks to torture and kill captives.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Advocates for the mentally ill and some psychiatrists such as Thomas Szasz have asserted that electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is torture when used without a *bona fide* medical benefit against recalcitrant or non-responsive patients.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] The Judge Rotenberg Center in Canton, Massachusetts, has been condemned for torture by the United Nations special rapporteur on torture for its use of electric shocks with the purpose of punishment as part of its behavior modification program.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Japanese serial killer Futoshi Matsunaga used electric shocks to control his victims.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Electric shock delivered by an electric chair is sometimes used as an official means of capital punishment in the United States, although its use has become rare from the 1990s onward due to the adoption of lethal injection.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Although some original proponents of the electric chair considered it to be a more humane execution method than hanging, shooting, poison gassing, etc., it has now generally been replaced by lethal injections in states that practice capital punishment.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Modern reporting has claimed that it sometimes takes several shocks to be lethal, and that the condemned person may actually catch fire before death.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] Other than in parts of the United States, only the Philippines reportedly has used this method, from 1926 to 1976.
[src:electrical-injury/electrical-injury] It was intermittently replaced by the firing squad, until the death penalty was abolished in that country.
